Introduction to agricultural instrumentsThere are 5 types of agricultural measure that you will need to be aware of, albeit not all are likely to be active in the UK tariff on day one. These are:


The Meursing table and Meursing codes
Unit prices or Simplified Procedural Values (SPVs)
The Entry Price System & Standard Import Values
Representative prices for chicken
Variable prices for cereals and rice

The Meursing table and Meursing codesAbout Meursing codes


Meursing codes are used in the EU to apply specific duties to compound agri-goods (the official term for delicious cakes and biscuits), depending on the relative content of sugar, flour and milk starch / solids.
Meursing codes were introduced to allow for cakes etc. to be taxed according to their ‘luxury’ value without there needing to be literally thousands of new commodity codes to be created to cater for the many permutations.
The EU has executed the revenue collection for such goods using Meursing additional codes.
For the best detailed view of Meursing codes, please see this blog by trade expert Peter Ungphakorn.

The Meursing table


The trader works out the constituent parts of sugar, butter etc, looks for the correct cell in the table to the right for their product’s recipe.
The then declares this number, prefaced by the Meursing identifier “7”, on their import declaration form, after which the duty is calculated in the border system.



https://www.gov.uk/additional-commodity-code
Working out your Meursing code

How do Meursing codes impact duty calculations?


In UK parlance, the component parts are displayed using the three terms:


AC – standing for “Agricultural Component”, means milk-based product (like butter)
SD – standing for “Sugar Duty”
FD – standing for “Flour Duty”

In the EU jurisdiction, these were respectively referred to as EA, ADSZ and ADFM, which are the French and German equivalents of AC, SD and FD (Elément agricole, Additional duties – Sucre Zucker, Additional duties – Farine, Mehl).
If a duty is displayed as 7.60% + EA (see product 1901200000 - right), this means that there is a simple ad valorem duty of 7.60% plus a variable component based on milk / butter content.
The trader can then look up the milk / butter content’s Meursing code, either by looking at the table, or by using the UK gov online service, and then work out the full duty.
Actually the EU’s Taric consultation is the best (until the end of the Implementation period), as the Meursing tool is semi-integrated into the standard tariff lookup.


Showing 3rd country (MFN) duty for  product 1901200000 (Malt extract) on the Trade Tariff Service
The duty is not just a simple ad valorem or a specific duty based on a weight (or other unit). Instead, the import duties will depend on the %age content of milk protein & milk fat.
https://www.trade-tariff.service.gov.uk/commodities/1901200000
Meursing additional codes


Meursing placeholders are ‘replaced’ by additional codes of a specific type (type 7)
Type 7 codes are stored in a different table from all other additional codes: it is not clear why
Duties are assigned to the Meursing additional codes, not the commodities that might use them in their measures.


How the EU Taric Consultation facilitates Meursing


On the EU Taric Consultation site, which will be of no relevance to us after the end of the Implementation Period, the Meursing functionality is embedded into the standard tariff lookup function.
Again, with example product 1901200000, the trader first sees  the duty 7.60% + EA(1) - picture 1
Then the trader either enters the %age components into a tool like the UK’s Meursing tool, or they enter the relevant 3 digit code from the Meursing table.
This then refreshes the page (picture 2) with an expanded duty. The specific duty of 117.85 EUR/100kg has been inserted to replace the “EA” placeholder
BTW – the (1) in brackets refers to something called the reduction indicator – see later


The future or Meursings … mixedThis is an extremely complex process for traders, and almost impossible to marshal for Border Force, therefore the UK had taken the decision to abandon the Meursing system for No Deal – this may be reversed for the end of the Implementation period.
Caveat 1 - While having no Meursing codes helps to simplify the UK tariff, it is only a partial saving grace, as there remains a requirement to include Meursing-related information in the reference document.
This is hugely problematic, as it defeats the point of using the actual UK tariff as the source for the reference document: the Meursing data needs to come from elsewhere – in this case from the live EU database. Perversely, if Meursings were to return, this would simplify document production.
Caveat 2 – anything stated now may not be true by the end of the Implementation period.
A recent Cabinet paper has identified that there will be a review of all agricultural instruments.
Some interest has been shown in a simplification of the Meursing table, e.g. reducing the columns and rows to more manageable & intelligible options, but is unlikely to have been agreed before Jan 2021.
Caveat 3 – the Northern Ireland Protocol means that NI traders in goods considered at risk will be subject to the full Union Customs Code (UCC), including the full set of applicable EU import duties.
Whether this is deliverable by 2021 is in doubt.But the UCC includes Meursing, therefore some UK traders, and DDaT and DIT Policy team will need to understand this subject in depth.It is not going away.
Setting measures against Meursing codes


Meursing codes break the mould in nearly every way. Everything you have learnt about the tariff, relearn it for Meursing codes.
First, these are the sole instances in the tariff of duties (measures and measure components) being assigned against an additional code alone, and not against a combination of commodity code and additional code.
The Image top right shows the absence of commodity code (goods_nomenclature_item_id) but presence of the Meursing additional code (7012)
The measure type of 674 indicates that this duty, once calculated with the specific ingredient percentages, will insert a duty to replace an EA (agricultural component) placeholder.
The duties assigned to this measure are highlighted in the image right bottom.
Read more about this in the measure components guide, which explains what all these fields mean in detail.
Basically this means “add a duty equal to 17.18 Euros per 100kg (1 decitonne)” to any measure that includes an EA placeholder, regardless of the commodity code.


Calculating Meursing duties on complex duties


Let’s take this as an example – this is commodity code 1704905500 Throat pastilles and cough drops with a screen grab taken from the Trade Tariff Service.
Yes, we apply duties based on sugar and butter content on throat lozenges, imported from the Faroe Islands.
The trader sees the duty  0.00 % + EA MAX 18.70 % +ADSZ
This reads (in English) as:
0.00% ad valorem (a reduction from the 9.00% of the MFN)
Plus the agricultural component supplement
Up to a maximum of 18.70% ad valorem …
Plus the sugar component
At this point the trader does not know the values that will replace EA and ADSZ, so they look up their ingredient %ages and come up with a Meursing additional code 7507.
The trader sends comm code 1704905500 and additional code 7507 to CDS / CHIEF and they replace the EA & ADSZ placeholders with real specific duties (which they all are).


Hence, 0.00% + EA up to a MAX of 18.70% +ADSZ
becomes
0.00% + 18.87 €/100kg up to a MAX of 18.70% + 99.88 €/100kg
when the recipe is added. To reiterate: Meursing duties are applicable to the recipe, not the commodity; but they are only chargeable when replacing the placeholders in comm code duties.
Meursing measure types & duty expressions

The reduction indicator and geographical areas


Meursing code measures are typically assigned to the geographical area ID 1011 (Erga Omnes, the whole world).
However, they can be assigned to other countries: in fact the following countries / groups have Meursing measures, allowing the EU to tailor duties to the individual countries:




So geographical areas add a further dimension to the management of Meursing-related duties.
Just when you thought it could not get any more complex, along comes the reduction indicator.
The table on the previous page showed a pair of duty expressions that can be related to a Meursing-type measure




The second of these pairs (reduced additional duty on sugar / flour / agricultural component) allows the EU to assign effectively a different Meursing table
The reduction indicator can only be applied to preferential duties – i.e. it is never assigned to Erga Omnes (1011).
The reason for the reduction indicator is to provide a reduction on the base (non-reduced duty) for certain ranges of goods from a given country.

Meursing tables – data structure

Meursing appears to have been tacked on to the basic tariff, as a lot of the principles that apply across the board otherwise have been abandoned.
Most importantly, although they are treated as additional codes in assigning measures, they are stored in separate tables from all other such codes (and transmitted to HMRC as such).
The standard “type 1” naming convention & data structure has also been eschewed: 
meursing_subgheadings contains the descriptions
meursing_heading_texts is used instead of the more standard meursing_heading_descriptioins
Unit prices (SPVs)

Unit price is a synonym for Simplified Procedural Value (SPV).
It is used for goods that are imported on consignment, i.e. they are yet to be sold, so they need a reference price to work out import duty and VAT.
The UK typically uses the term SPV, the EU typically uses the term Unit Price, but they are interchangeable.
Traders can only use the SPV scheme for whole fruit and vegetable produce, of a single kind, imported on a consignment basis.
SPVs are customs values derived from prices at which goods were sold on sales in specified markets within Europe. The prices gathered from across the EU are combined (through a process that is not understood in DIT) to form a single “Unit price”
Unit prices are used on certain fruit and vegetables only (54 commodity codes at the time of writing)
Excluded from the scheme are fruit or vegetable products that have undergone a cut and dicing process prior to importation.
SPVs are updated by the EU fortnightly, starting midnight Thursday / Friday, while the UK still needs to work out the frequency with which we will update these values.
For SPVs (and SIVs) the unit of measure is always DTN (100kg or decitonne).

Examples of commodity codes that are assigned Unit Prices are: garlic, cauliflowers, asparagus, carrots, peas, aubergine, celery, sweet peppers, beans as well as soft fruit such as plums, peaches, nectarines, strawberries etc.
Future of the SPV & currency usage


The SPV is expected to be widely used in the UK Tariff post-implementation period, as the requirement to divine a price for goods delivered on consignment will persist.
Work will be required to understand how often the SPVs are to be updated (every 2 weeks in the EU).
SPV are and will remain without exception aimed at Erga Omnes (1011 – the whole world) – there are no preferential instances of SPVs.
SPVs use measure type 488 (Unit Price)
There are never any conditions associated with an SPV, just components identifying the specific import duty (e.g. 184.58 EUR (EUC) / 100 kg)
It is not clear why the EU uses the monetary unit EUC instead of just EUR. EUC stands for “Euro, according to Article 146 (2) of Regulation (EC) No 2015/2447”. This document is the EU legislation underpinning the UCC (Union Customs Code), and hints at the reason (right - i.e. usage of monthly conversion factor).
There remain outstanding questions on the future of currency in the management of import duties: EUROs will remain for the time being but may be replaced by sterling at some stage in the future.

CHAPTER 3 - Currency conversion 
Article 48 - Provisions on tariff exchange rate (Article 53 of the Code) 
1. The value of the euro, where required in accordance with Article 53(1)(b) of the Code, shall be fixed once a month. 
The exchange rate to be used shall be the most recent rate set by the European Central Bank prior to the penultimate day of the month and shall apply throughout the following month. 
However, where the rate applicable at the start of the month differs by more than 5 % from the rate set by the European Central Bank prior to the 15th of that same month, the latter rate shall apply from the 15th until the end of the month in question.


Where the conversion of currency is necessary for any of the reasons referred to in Article 53(2) of the Code, the value of the euro in national currencies to be applied shall be the rate set by the European Central Bank on the first working day of October; this rate shall apply with effect from 1 January of the following year.
Member States may maintain unchanged the value in national currency of the amount determined in euro if, at the time of the annual adjustment, the conversion of that amount, leads to an alteration of less than 5 % in the value expressed in national currency. 
Member States may round upwards or downwards to the nearest decimal point the sum arrived at after conversion 

The Entry Price System & SIVs

The EU protects growers of 15 kinds of selected fruits and vegetables against international competition not only by the means of ad valorem tariffs of up to 20%, but also by the EPS.
The EPS came into effect on 1 July 1995
Analogous to a minimum import price, the EPS is designed to restrict imports below the product-specific, politically designated EP plus ad valorem tariff.
If the EP is undercut, an additional specific tariff is levied, which proportionally varies depending on the gap between the product’s actual import price and the EP.
When the EP is undercut by 8% or more, the maximum specific tariff, referred to as the maximum tariff equivalent (MTE), of up to 80% of the EP is charged.
For example, the EPS is applied to oranges during the EU orange harvest season in the time period December 1 to May 31.
The MFN tariff for oranges seasonally varies between 3.2% and 16.0% whereas the MFN EP remains constant at a level of 354 €/t.
If oranges are exported to the EU at a price of 336.3 €/t, the EP is undercut by 5%.
This implies that the exporter has to pay an additional specific tariff of 17.7 €/t which is equal to the gap between the import price and the EP.
If the entry price for oranges is undercut by 8% or more, an additional specific tariff at the level of the MTE of 71 €/t is charged.

Standard Import Values (SIVs)


Monitoring compliance with the EPS faces the difficulty that a large share of fruit and vegetable imports in the EU is on commission, implying that the import price is not determined until the product is sold in the EU market.
Therefore, the European Commission calculates a synthetic import price, the standard import value (SIV).
Fruit and vegetable prices, surveyed for each product and export country individually, are collected on representative fruit and vegetable wholesale markets in all EU Member States (for example New Covent Garden Market in the UK).
The daily SIVs are calculated as a weighted average of collected wholesale market prices, less a marketing and transportation margin and applied tariffs.
DIT has not been made aware of the specific calculations that will be undertaken to manage the SIV, as this is a Defra responsibility
It is also not 100% clear as to what the future of the SIV in the UK will be, not for that matter the Entry Price System as a whole.
The EPS was designed as a protectionist measure for EU growers – during growing season they had to sell their goods or see them rot: outside that season, the EPS is not applied. The UK does not have the same climate, nor therefore the same agricultural sensibilities.




Therefore the expectation is that the EPS will be abandoned in the UK (needs to be validated, and may well change through the Transition Period).
However, the SIV must stay for tax calculation and reporting purposes.

The SIV without the Entry Price System


If there is no Entry Price System, then the SIV will need to persist regardless. This is because it offers traders a way of valuing their goods for import duty and VAT calculation perspective.
Let’s say a consignment of sweet oranges arrives from overseas to be sold on New Covent Garden Market. At the point of arrival into the UK, it does not have a sale price.
And yet, there will possibly be a desire to impose some kind of import duty (dependent on trade policy) and there will also be a desire to calculate a VAT surcharge.
In actual fact, VAT on such goods in the UK is 0% and the likelihood of the UK imposing import duties on goods we do not grow in the UK (to industrial volumes) is small, therefore the taxation & revenue aspect of the SIV is apparently negligible.
However, the VAT calculation still needs to know the ‘value’ of the goods to do its 0% calculation, therefore some yardstick (the SIV) is required.
Moreover for reporting purposes, the SIV allows statistical analysis of the value of imports to be carried out: without a nominal value this would not be possible.
One could argue that, without the Entry Price System, the SIV is precisely the same as the SPV (Unit Price), as the purpose, mechanic and impact would be identical.
However they are legislated for separately and the UK is reserving the right to bring back the EPS, therefore the distinction is likely to remain.
Defra need to be consulted on this, as it is a changing area

The relationship of SIVs to SPV


There are 7 commodity codes (data from 2019), where both SIVs and SPVs apply (below).
The two pivot tables to the right show the usage of SPVs and SIVs throughout a year on commodity code 0805102200 (Sweet oranges).
The tables show that the SIV applies while the EPS is running (in the EU) and the SPV applies when it does not, according to European growing (marketing) seasons. SPV and SIV are never concurrent on the same commodity code.


SIVs and key origins


The Entry Price Systems is not one-size fits all. There are multiple countries which have specific SIVs that differ from the SIV applied to MFNs (this is never the case with SPVs).
For example, on the commodity to the right (Monreales – 0805220011 [a type of clementine]), there are multiple geography-specific SIV rates, as per the image to the right, showing the applicable measures for Israel (which has its own SIV for monreales), compares to the SIV for Erga Omnes (bottom right).
This is a reflection of the prices of goods when they are gathered in the EU markets on a per origin basis.
The following slide shows the countries which have their own SIV values (2019 Jan 1st onwards).
Erga Omnes (1011) has full coverage, while other nations’ SIVs are very specific, e.g. for Australia, the EU has SIVs solely for apples



The Entry Price System in Action


The screen grab to the right shows a fragment of the page on the Trade Tariff Service for the import of Cider apples (0808108010).
There are two rows that are interesting. First, the SIV itself for Erga Omnes
Secondly, the third country duty – in most cases, a third country duty is not conditional: it is applicable to all trades in goods from non-preferential zones.
On goods where the EPS applies, the third country duty is dependent on the import price, which, if the good is brought in on consignment, may be determined by the SIV.





Clicking on “Conditions” shows the condition mechanic – this is described in more detail in the guide on measure conditions, but the meaning of this page is as per the preamble on the workings of the EPS.
The applicable duties for the import of a good are inversely proportional to the declared import price – i.e. the lower the import price, the higher the duties, according to pre-set thresholds.
The duty is expressed in terms of a flat ad valorem and a specific: typically it is just the specific duty which changes, though here, if the good is imported at a very low price, then the duties are waived entirely.
The system is tightly balanced, showing the precarious nature of Southern European agri-business, with the thresholds being respectively 98, 96, 92, 90, 88 and 86% of the zero-duty reference price.


Representative prices for poultry

Representative Prices for Poultry are a type of special agricultural safeguard, protecting the domestic market from influx of cheap imports of poultry products at high volume.
The world chicken market is highly competitive and there are certain countries which would be able to gain a complete hegemony in poultry trade if safeguards were not applied. In the world of poultry, Argentina, Brazil, Chile and Thailand are far and away the biggest exporters and therefore these safeguard measures are applied solely to their exports.
Representative prices differ for different origins. While these have been calculated by DG Agri in the European Commission, and the UK has been able to vote on the representative prices, we nor other individual member states are involved in the calculation, nor understand how they are calculated.
Representative prices an be raised at any time and the prices and trigger tiers are modified regularly (once a month for chicken products).
There are also representative price measures for molasses, but this function has been dormant for a number of years, therefore does not need to be considered for the UK tariff.

How Representative Prices work


The concept behind representative prices for poultry is very similar to the Entry Price System for Fruit and Vegetables, however there are a number of additional operational challenges that traders face in importing goods against this regime.
To the right is a view of the measures that are associated with the import of boneless chicken cuts (0207141000) from Argentina.
All 5 of these measures contribute to the duties and securities that will be required of a chicken importer.
Under a No Deal, this trade safeguard would have been abandoned in the UK, but it is potentially back on the table.




The first measure to be looked at is the representative price measure itself (measure type 489).




This is similar in purpose to the Standard Import Value measure (490) used for fruit & veg – it sets an expected acceptable import price for a good.
As per the regulation covering this, which is refreshed on a regular basis in the EU:
The representative prices […] shall be determined at regular intervals (monthly) taking into account in particular:


the prices on third country markets
free-at-Community-frontier offer prices
prices at the various stages of marketing in the Community for imported products.

The importer may choose to use the “representative price” method to calculate import duty on their goods.
Or, at the request of the importer, the additional duty may be established on the basis of the CIF import price of the consignment in question, if this price is higher than the applicable representative price.
The application of the CIF (cost, insurance & freight) import price of the consignment for establishing the additional duty is subject to the presentation of multiple documents including the purchasing contract (to prove value).
The importer must lodge a security (deposit)  equal to the amount of additional duty which he would have paid if the calculation of the additional duty had been made on the basis of the representative price applicable to the product in question.
So here is the second of the five measures explained (measure type 653):




Essentially, border authorities do not trust that the goods being brought in are going to be sold at the value documented on the purchasing contract: securities are lodged until the importer can prove that they are not lying.
The importer has one month from the sale of the products in question to prove that the consignment was disposed of at the stated price.
Failure to meet the deadline means they lose the security lodged. But if they can prove sale conditions matched those declared, then securities are returned.


How to calculate applicable duties


If the difference between the (representative) trigger price and the import price:
 is less than or equal to 10 % of the trigger price, no additional duty shall be imposed;
 is greater than 10 % but less than or equal to 40 % of the trigger price, the additional duty shall equal 30 % of the amount by which the difference exceeds 10 %;
is greater than 40 % but less than or equal to 60 % of the trigger price, the additional duty shall equal 50 % of the amount by which the difference exceeds 40 %, plus the additional duty allowed under (b);
is greater than 60 % but less than or equal to 75 %, the additional duty shall equal 70 % of the amount by which the difference exceeds 60 % of the trigger price, plus the additional duties allowed under (b) and ©;
is greater than 75 % of the trigger price, the additional duty shall equal 90 % of the amount by which the difference exceeds 75 %, plus the additional duties allowed under (b), © and (d).
So here is the third measure that is applied – measure type 652, Additional duty based on cif price.


We actually do not need to worry too much about this calculation, but at least it helps to clarify the stepped thresholds applied on such conditional measures.

Duty calculation using measure conditions
The five thresholds that were noted on the previous page (derived from the controlling EU regulation) are represented by measure conditions with price thresholds.
The mechanisms are almost identical to the Entry Price’s thresholds (which use condition code V). These use condition code L, which essentially references the CIF price instead.
Duties are then applied in inverse relation to the declared import price.

Reducing representative prices under quota


The final two measures allow a trade in poultry under representative prices to be reduced by way of a quota – or, in this case, two licensed quotas for the import of poultry products.
This sets a further threshold whereby the representative price and associated securities do not kick in until the quota is exhausted / licences allocated and used.
These quotas behave much in the way of existing quotas, but do use specialised measure types (653 and 654)


Prognosis for representative prices


Under No Deal, representative prices for chicken would have been dumped as a trade instrument. However, as a consultation is now going out to ask traders what they think of the EU tariff, all best are off.
The UK may be required to support this function, hence the detailed explanation

Variable duties for rice and cereals
Situation in the EU
The types of cereals covered by this system are: durum wheat, high quality common wheat, rye, maize, sorghum.
The duty to be applied will be the difference between an EU reference price of €157.03/tonne (155% of the EU intervention price) and the cost of delivering the consignment in question to an EU port (including cost, insurance and freight). However, that duty may not exceed the WTO bound rate of duty set out in the Common Customs Tariff. 
The Commission carry out a daily calculation, though the rate fixes if not changed significantly against mean for 10 days.

UK prognosis
It is likely that the UK will not vary duties on cereals, but will retain the legal capability.
Import duties set by route into the Union


The screen grab to the right shows commodity code 1007900000 (Grain sorghum – a type of millet)
You can see that there are 3 additional codes assigned to the commodity code that must be used by traders in these goods to identify the route taken to get the goods into the Union.
You can also see that the duties are all 0.00%, meaning that the differentiation is of little value.
In fact, variable duties for cereals exists in name & (dormant) legislative power only – the EU has not operationalised these powers for some time, and the UK has (at the last count) no intention of operationalising it.
As always with agri measures, please keep close to the situation in case it changes. We are likely to legislate for this, but not use it in anger.


Variable duty for rice

Situation in the EU
Currently includes Husked (brown) rice (excluding husked basmati rice), Semi-milled/milled (white) rice.
Import duties for husked and semi-milled/milled rice are fixed on the basis of the level of import licences issued in the preceding 12 and 6 month period respectively.
Rice Marketing year runs from 1 September – 31 August
This is executed in the tariff as a standard Third country tariff.

Prognosis for the UK
As with ‘variable’ duties for cereals, this simply does not change frequently: in addition, as this solely uses simple third country duties (type 103), there is no special mechanism for DDaT or tariff managers to be concerned with.

11.title: Unilateral preferences
11.content:
Unilateral PreferencesWhat are unilateral preferences?


As the name suggests, unilateral preferences represent favourable treatment afforded to third countries under certain circumstances with no expectation that the providing country will get any preferential treatment / market access in return.
Many developed nations have adopted one form or another of a unilateral preference programme in order to remove or reduce import duties from products coming into their domestic market from vulnerable developing countries. This helps developing countries to alleviate poverty and create jobs based on international values and principles, including labour and human rights.
The EU has approached this goal by adopting the idea of the Generalised System of Preferences (GSP): the UK will adopt this after EU Exit.


Generalised System of Preferences (GSP)


The Generalised System of Preferences (GSP), instituted in 1971 under the aegis of UNCTAD (United Nations Conference on Trade and Development), has contributed over the years to creating an enabling trading environment for developing countries.
The following 13 countries/blocs grant GSP preferences: Australia, Belarus, Canada, the European Union, Iceland, Japan, Kazakhstan, New Zealand, Norway, the Russian Federation, Switzerland, Turkey and the United States of America.

Three GSP tiers

Ownership of Unilateral Preferences


The primary remit for Unilateral Preferences falls to DFID, the Department for International Development.
There is then a dotted line into DIT and a very close working relationship.


About Standard GSP (GSP General Framework)
Standard GSP reduces EU import duties for about 66% of all product tariff lines.

Conditions


Any developing country will benefit from Standard GSP unless:


it has another type of special trade access to the EU granting the same tariff preferences as the scheme, or better, for substantially all trade
it has achieved a high- or upper-middle income economy status during three consecutive years according to the World Bank classification


The EU can withdraw Standard GSP in exceptional circumstances, notably serious and systematic violation of fundamental human rights and labour rights conventions.

Product graduation


Some developing countries export highly competitive products, which do not need preferences to successfully access world markets (e.g. India and Indonesia).
In that case GSP is withdrawn from these product sectors through a graduation mechanism (see EU website for details)
The EU reviews the list of graduated products every three years through an implementing regulation and on the basis of objective criteria.
The UK will adopt all of these features post-Implementation period.
Product graduation only applies to the General Framework, not the other two tiers.

Tariff reduction under GSP Standard Framework is rules-driven


The import duties applicable to countries trading on GSP Standard Framework are not negotiated or subject to whim
They are calculated as percentages of the prevailing MFN, according to the type of product
The EU’s “REGULATION (EU) No 978/2012 OF THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND OF THE COUNCIL of 25 October 2012 applying a scheme of generalised tariff preferences and repealing Council Regulation (EC) No 732/2008” explains this rather well.
This regulation differentiates between sensitive and non-sensitive products: sensitive products being those that are key to sectors within the EU’s manufacturing base.
Common Customs Tariff duties on non-sensitive products are suspended in full, while duties on sensitive products enjoy a tariff reduction.
ad valorem duties are generally be reduced by a flat rate of 3.5 percentage points from the ‘most favoured nation’ duty rate, while ad valorem duties for textiles and textile goods are reduced by 20%.
Specific duties are reduced by 30 %.
Where a minimum duty is specified, that minimum duty does not apply.
Duties are suspended totally, where the preferential treatment for an individual import declaration results in an ad valorem duty of 1 % or less or in a specific duty of EUR 2 or less, since the cost of collecting such duties might be higher than the revenue gained.
While this is rules-driven, the complexity of building a rules-driven service for the Tariff Application is yet to be attempted. This will feature on the backlog at some time.

Beneficiaries of GSP General Framework
The following countries are beneficiaries of the GSP General Framework – this is the list of countries that would have gone live in a November 2019 No Deal for GSP General Framework.

About GSP+ (GSP Enhanced Framework)
The special incentive arrangement for Sustainable Development and Good Governance GSP+ grants full removal of tariffs on over 66% of EU tariff lines.

Conditions
To be eligible for GSP+, the country must lodge an application and fulfil the Standard GSP conditions and the following two additional criteria:


Vulnerability criteria
In order to qualify for GSP+, a beneficiary country has to fulfil the vulnerability criteria – the country must be recognised as globally weak in terms of export on goods subject to GSP+ reductions and sufficiently diverse in its export capability across GSP+ categories
Sustainable development criteria
The country must have ratified the 27 GSP+ relevant international conventions on human- and labour rights, environmental protection and good governance.


Monitoring
Once a country is granted GSP+, the EU monitors that the beneficiary country abides by its commitments

Beneficiary countries
The following countries will be members of GSP+


Armenia
Bolivia
Cape Verde
Kyrgyzstan
Mongolia
Pakistan
Philippines
Sri Lanka

About Everything But Arms EBA (GSP LDC Framework)


Everything but Arms (EBA) is an initiative of the European Union under which all imports to the EU from the Least Developed Countries are duty-free and quota-free, with the exception of armaments. EBA entered into force on 5 March 2001.
Arms are available in Chapter 93 of the goods classification (under the harmonised system), meaning that every one of the other chapters 91 to 98, except chapter 77) is duty- and quota-free.
A country is being granted EBA status if it is listed as a Least Developed Country (LDC) by the UN Committee for Development Policy.
Countries do not need to apply to benefit from EBA, they are added or removed to relevant list through a delegated regulation.
EBA preferences can be withdrawn in case of some exceptional circumstances, notably in case of serious and systematic violation of principles laid down in fundamental human rights and labour rights conventions (see article 19 of Regulation (978/2012).
Unlike under the Standard GSP, countries do not lose EBA status by entering into a Free Trade Agreement with the EU. A ‘graduation mechanism’ for products also does not apply.


Volatility of GSP frameworks


Countries do move in and out of GSP frameworks as their economies progress or recede, or if they fail to adhere to conditions of membership, e.g. human rights.
However these changes are both rare and predictable, as they are telegraphed months or years ahead of the event.
The following changes have occurred recently:


Equatorial Guinea will leave its current lowly ranking in the LDC category and exit GSP altogether in December 2020, as it has been classified by the world-bank as a high income economy in 2015 and as an upper-middle income economy in 2016 and 2017.
Samoa joined the general framework on Jan 1st 2019, having been ‘promoted’ from LDC.
Paraguay left the GSP scheme altogether on Dec 31st 2018, as the country has been classified by the World Bank as upper-middle income country in 2015, 2016 and 2017
Ghana left the GSP scheme altogether on Dec 31st 2018
Swaziland (Eswatini) left the GSP scheme altogether on Dec 31st 2018
Côte d’Ivoire left the GSP scheme altogether on Dec 31st 2018


Economic Partnership Agreements (EPAs)


Economic Partnership Agreements (EPAs) are trade and development agreements negotiated between the EU and African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) partners, aimed at promoting trade and to foster sustainable development and poverty reduction.
In actual fact, EPAs are identical in nature to the EU’s FTAs and are discussed in that document: they are discussed here due to joint ownership with DFID and the sustainability / developmental nature of their being.
The UK will adopt all of these, though the component countries will depend on who signs when, and the international political standing of these states – for example, it is not thought that the Comoros Islands will be included in the ESA EPA.
The following EPAs exist:


Central Africa (Cameroon)
Eastern and Southern Africa (Comoros, Madagascar, Mauritius, Seychelles , Zimbabwe)
East African Community (Kenya)
Southern African Development Community (Botswana, Lesotho, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa and Eswatini)
West Africa (Côte d'Ivoire and Ghana)
Caribbean (CARIFORUM)
Pacific (Fiji, Samoa and Papua New Guinea)

See https://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/countries-and-regions/development/economic-partnerships/index_en.htm for more

Transitional Protection Measure (TPM)


The TPM or Transitional Protection Measure was to be put in place prior to the previous No Deals to make up for the fact that there had been insufficient time to transition a number of EPAs with African states.
While the fundaments had not been agreed, it was felt that to leave these states, some of which are members of the Commonwealth, with no advantageous trade deal, would be a political own goal.
The countries that would have joined the TPM are:


Cameroon
Côte D’Ivoire (Ivory Coast)
Ghana
Kenya 
Zimbabwe

It remains to be seen if there is a need for the TPM at the end of the Implementation Period – it may well be that all EPAs have been transitioned.
The nature of the EPAs is, from a tariff duty perspective, identical to Everything But Arms (EBA) as applies to the LDC countries, i.e. full tariff removal on all goods except weaponry (chapter 93).

Unilateral preference measures


All GSP measures are essentially tariff preferences – of type 142 and 145
The fact that they are unilateral makes no difference to the Tariff.
142 = standard tariff preference measure
145 = tariff preference under end use (authorised use)

12.title: Free trade agreements
12.content:
Free trade agreements


Tariff preference measures


Preferential quota measures


The EU’s Free Trade Agreements and Economic Partnership Agreements

Individual Trade Agreements (EU)


The world map on the previous page shows the Trade Agreements with whom the EU has Trade Agreements of one form or another – the map simplifies the distinction between the types of agreement, as the distinction is not relevant to the management of the regulations in the UK tariff. Even the EBA distinction makes zero difference to how data is managed.
Below is a list of the 40 blocs with which the EU has agreements (Vietnam expected in 2020). Some of these agreements incorporate trading blocs or more informally grouped countries - these groupings are discussed below. Some are special (looking at you Iceland and Norway). 
Though Trade Agreements happen rarely and do not creep up unannounced, they are likely to be time-consuming to implement.


Trading groups / blocs
thus table details the countries which belong to the various trade groups and hints at their probable treatment in the UK tariff.

        
          
Andean
CARIFORUM
Central America
EAC
ESA
EEA
Pacific
SACU-M
Switzerland + Liechtenstein


Each   of the countries in the Andean agreement are dealt with separately in the UK   and have very different tariffs and quotas applied
Treated   as a single trading bloc, all duties apply as one – just tariff preferences,   no quotas. Haiti is formally a member but excluded from all measures (not yet   ratified)
The   tariff preferences for each of these 6 countries are shared using the C.   America group ID (2200). There are a few shared quotas, some excluding   Panama, then individual quotas per country
This   is a great example of where formal trading blocs operate effectively   independently. The bloc features Burundi, Kenya, Rwanda, Tanzania, and   Uganda, but only Kenya has ratified.
All   tariff preferences are applied equally – watch out for Mauritius-specific   quotas.   Comoros   is likely to be excluded by the UK (check)
The   EEA is bigger than just Norway and Iceland, but that is all that will apply   in the UK’s interpretation of the EEA (e.g. Liechtenstein is omitted). Norway   and Iceland merit their own page.
Please   check with the EPA / FTA team on the UK future status of Samoa – it has   formally joined this group in the EU, but it is not clear if it will join the   UK EPA.
Stands   for Southern African Customs Union and Mozambique.
Decision   was taken that Liechtenstein would not benefit from EEA duties, but would   receive precisely the same duties as Switzerland.


Colombia   Ecuador   Peru
Antigua   and Barbuda     Barbados     Bahamas     Belize     Dominica     Dominican   Republic     Grenada     Guyana     Haiti     Jamaica     St   Kitts and Nevis     St.   Lucia     Suriname     Trinidad   and Tobago     St   Vincent and the Grenadines
Costa   Rica   El   Salvador   Guatemala   Honduras   Nicaragua   Panama
Kenya
Comoros (excluding Mayotte)   Madagascar   Mauritius   Seychelles and dependencies   Zimbabwe
Norway   Iceland
Papua   New Guinea   Fiji   Samoa   (?)
South   Africa   Botswana   Lesotho   Namibia   Eswatini   1   Mozambique
Switzerland   Liechtenstein


        
      What do Trade Agreements contain?


There are really only two major entities that trade agreements contain: tariff preferences and tariff rate quotas.
These are the core components of a Trade Agreement and the vehicles by which Tariff barriers are removed and reduced.
It is also possible that trade agreements also include some restrictions and may also feature supplementary units, but these are minor components.


Preferential tariffs / tariff preferences (either works)


These allow traders to import goods from an overseas nation at a reduced or zero duty rate, provided they can prove that the goods are materially derived from that nation, according to the rule of origin described in the associated legislation.


Preferential Tariff Rate Quotas (TRQs)


Preferential TRQs are included in over half the trade agreements that we will be carrying over to the UK: typically it is the EPAs, which are either full EBA or close to EBA that do not have quotas, as the duties are already 0%
TRQs and tariff preferences on the same commodity code are perfectly possible – for example in the Peru trade agreement, there are both tariff preferences and a quota on pork products (e.g. commodity 0203295520)
It is down to


a) is there quota balance available?
b) how they complete their SAD form

Individual commodity codes may belong to multiple quota order numbers (e.g. Kosovan wines belong to multiple preferential quotas)

Rules of Origin
The EU (and in the future the UK) has rules for establishing the country of origin of imported and exported goods. Traders need them to classify goods manufactured in more than one country.

Defining the origin


There are 2 main categories of origin in the rules:


goods wholly obtained or produced in a single country
goods whose production involved materials from more than one country

The second category is the more complex as there are several criteria to consider – e.g. the origins of the materials, the country in which the final substantial production phase took place and the value the working and processing in each country has added.
If a product is manufactured entirely in the EU and is exported to a country with which there is a preferential arrangement it may attract lower or nil rates of duty when it is imported into the destination country.
If some of the components are manufactured in the EU but components are added and the product is assembled in another country it may be judged that the product originates from the country where it is assembled. The duty requirement will depend on the arrangements between the country in which the product was assembled and the country into which it will be imported.


Proof of origin


Traders who want to import goods at a reduced or nil preferential rate of duty (for bi-partite or unilateral preferences) must get proof of origin in the form of a EUR-1 or EUR-MED certificate, which needs to be completed by the exporter and presented to the border authorities at export and import.

Rules of origin and the tariff


Oddly, there is very little in the Tariff that requests a proof of origin.
One would have expected all measures from preferential agreements to be linked to proofs of origin, but they are not
One less thing to worry about

Concept - staging


The first thing to say is that the term “Free Trade Agreement” is often used optimistically to refer to any kind of preferential trade agreement. The term free trade suggests complete removal of tariffs on all goods, which, even in Everything But Arms Economic Partnership Agreements (EBA EPAs) / Generalised System of Preferences for Least Developed Countries (GSP LDC) is not the case.
But freer trade and de-tariffication is the ultimate goal of Trade Agreements.
This is usually achieved via a process called staging.
Staging can be applied to both tariff preferences and to tariff rate quotas in slightly different ways.


Preferential tariff staging
Trade Agreements will often aim to decrease tariff barriers over a number of years, in order to build in some protection for domestic producers. A common scenario is for a period of reduction to be set (e.g. 4 or 5 years), over which the duty rates are reduced from the prevailing MFN to

Tariff rate quota staging
Alternatively, many trade agreements contain recourse for preferential quotas where the volume of goods permitted into free circulation at a reduced in-quota rate increases by a set amount per year, as specified in the regulation that underpins the quotas.
The ultimate (but not quiet achievable) goal is to remove tariff barriers entirely.
Staging of tariff preferences


To the right are two fragments from the EU / Singapore Trade Agreement: the prose talks of the theory behind what is to be achieved and the split of commodities into staging categories. The table illustrates a set of commodities that are assigned to a given staging category and a bare rate from which the rate will reduce
For category 5 commodities, as per bullet (b), “customs duties on originating goods provided for in the items in staging category ‘5’ in a Party’s Schedule shall be removed in six equal stages beginning on the date this Agreement enters into force, and such goods shall thereafter be free of any customs duty”
Both the ad valorem and specific duties are reduced in roughly equal chunks over the course of the reduction period. Here is an example from Colombia, where the staging has just run its course (product 0402109100). The jumps are not quite equal though – you cannot programme for this!



https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:22019A1114(01)&from=EN#page=128
Staging of tariff rate quotas


Contrary to tariff preference staging, the aim of TRQ staging is not quite to get to absolute zero, though in some cases the quota can disappear altogether at the end of a specified period.
This differentiation between choosing quotas and preferences and, by extension, staging in the two, depends on the sensitivity of the goods in question and the presence of domestic suppliers.
The fifth column in the Trade Agreement reference document for Colombia (right) shows the modification that is made to the quota, i.e. more volume is made available per annum at 0.00% duties, with the overall net effect that tariff barriers are removed (when volume permitted exceeds likely trade flow).



FTA regulations are almost always wrong


Trade Agreements can take years from inception to ratification and operationalisation. Once they are published, potentially even in draft form, they are rarely if ever re-opened.
To the right is the same screen grab of the EU / Singapore trade agreement used earlier in this deck. Singapore Trade Agreement went live in November 2019.
The red marquee shows the digits CN13, meaning that the commodity codes used in the legal document and its tariff schedule are from the EU’s Combined Nomenclature of 2013 (6 years before actual go-live).
This is because the FTA has been negotiated since March 2010 and the negotiations on goods and services were completed in 2012.


The moral of the story is – don’t go looking in EU Trade Agreements for the gospel truth – they are almost always out of date.
The situation much worse with older agreements, such as Switzerland, where virtually no commodity codes in the legal text match the reality.
The Trade Agreement Continuity (TAC) Programme


The TAC (or Trade Agreement Continuity) programme in DIT has been run since the Referendum with the sole purpose of ‘rolling over’ as many of the existing EU trade agreements into the UK as possible.
The approach of rolling over Trade Agreements, i.e. not changing anything substantive, was seen as a necessary expedient, due to the shortage of time, and also to try to avoid potential challenges at the WTO, whose members would undoubtedly feel the need to scrutinise anything more than ‘technical changes’, or small changes to numbers
So, given there are two aspects to trade agreements, preferences and quotas, the UK is keeping preferences largely as-is and modifying quota balances to be more inline with the UK’s part of the bigger EU share.


Working out quota balances


In general a calculation is made of three years’ worth of quota usage in the UK and the EU to determine what size of quota pot should be assigned to the UK.
For example, if it was found that over three years, the UK used 15% of the EU’s overall allocation on the quotas in a trade agreement, and a given EU’s quota was 1 million tonnes, then the UK’s equivalent quota would be 150,000 tonnes.
This quota coefficient is worked out on an agreement-by-agreement basis, rather than quota-by-quota. Thus, that 15% would apply to all quotas in an agreement if 15% is the mean.
Not all quotas are considered relevant to the UK – expect a number of quotas to drop off completely if there has been no or little use of them by the UK.

Norway and Iceland



The EU trade relationship with the EEA (European Economic Area) is complex and very different from how the UK will treat its members.
For a start, EEA from a trade perspective contains Norway, Iceland and Liechtenstein. The EU countries themselves are also members of the EEA, though, being part of a single customs area, the duties and most regulatory controls do not apply.
The UK will treat Liechtenstein exactly as it treats Switzerland and will not treat it as part of the EEA, with which we will have no all-encompassing relationship as a trading bloc.
It is not clear what the position of the UK in relation to the EEA will be in the future.


Existing EU measures for Iceland and Norway


Iceland measures are assigned to three different geographical areas, as follows:


2012 – European Economic Area
2014 – European Economic Area (Iceland)
IS – Iceland

Norway measures are assigned to two different geographical areas, as follows:


2012 – European Economic Area
NO – Iceland

It is up to the trader to enter the origin of their choosing when declaring the import: they will usually choose the most preferential import duty


What the UK intends to do


The UK aims to simplify the relationship with these countries, but doing so is a complex data challenge.
The rule is that we adopt the most preferential rate from the options, and apply that, shelving the ‘worse’ options.
This is more complex that it sounds, due to the fact that the duties are applied at multiple levels in the category hierarchy and inherited down, thus the work we need to do to work out the ‘best’ duty requires us to expand the duties through the full hierarchy and essentially assign duties at end-line level, before raising the duties back up as high as possible in the hierarchy to reduce the data imprint and future management overhead.
See migration guide for more info.

Tariff preference measures

Tariff preference measures are assigned to commodities using measure types:


“142” Tariff preference and
“145” Preference under end-use (authorised use)1

You will find that trade agreements come in a very wide variety – from the EBA-style agreements (the EPAs) to the complex agreements such as Israel and Canada which come with all sorts of duty permutations.
The tariff manager will need to adopt different data management strategies to manage these different types of agreements:


a Fiji or Cameroon agreement could be completed in minutes, whereas Canada could take several days

Please review the document on measure components for information on how measures are constructed

Preferential quota measures

Preferential tariff measures are integrated using the two measure types:


143 - Preferential tariff quota
146 - Preferential tariff quota under end use

See the section on quotas for more information on what makes up a quota
End use quotas are applied to a very restricted range of commodities currently:


Tomatoes, cucumbers, fish, tomatoes, herring, cane or beet sugar and plum purée
Each of these is accompanied by the condition for a EUS - Authorisation for the use of end use procedure certificate

13.title: Miscellaneous measures
13.content:
Miscellaneous measures


Supplementary units


Credibility checks


Surveillance measures


SAD guidance & credibility checks, monitoring measure types



These measures are not responsible for imposing duties or prohibitions of restrictions, but they are critical to the monitoring of the EU tariff.
Supplementary units are set up to ensure that traders define the ‘quantity / size’ of their trade in more than just kilogrammes, which is the default. This information is then used for statistical purposes and for credibility checks.
Credibility checks are set up by the EU to ensure that traders do not submit incorrect declarations, by picking up on frequently made errors and blocking such erroneous declarations
Surveillance and monitoring is carried out for multiple reasons, e.g. for statistical analysis of trade flows

Supplementary units

There are three measure types which are used to define the additional unit that traders must include on their declaration form, if this is specified in the Tariff.
These are required to be specified for statistical tracking  purposes and / or to ensure that certain credibility checks are undertaken.
The following measure types are available:


109 Supplementary unit
110 Supplementary unit (import)
111 Supplementary unit (export)

111 has never been used, while the others have been used extensively. 109 is by far the more common of the two, and is used when the unit is to be applied to both imports and exports.
110 is applied when the unit is to be applied solely to the import of goods.


Supplementary unit will continue after the end of the Implementation period and will remain the responsibility of DIT MTPO.
Supplementary units - detail
Supplementary units are non-volatile, unique and simple. Such a measure, of any of the three types, is set up as follows:



The three data items highlighted in yellow above are critical here.
The duty_expression_ID field has a value of 99, which means that the expression is a supplementary unit
The measure type ID in the measures table identifies that this is a supplementary unit: it will nearly always be of type 109.
The measurement_unit_code field in the measure_components table will identify the unit that the trader has to submit on their declaration form – here, NAR means “Number of items”, which also applies to other ‘semantically’ similar units, such as number of head for cattle.
The measurement_unit_qualifier_code field is almost always null, but may be used to qualify the primary unit (e.g. KGM E)

Credibility checks

The EU Commission was not satisfied that the Member States were applying the right quality of checks on the declarations coming into their countries, so they centrally imposed measures to help assure quality – and imposed measures to check on the member states. These are called credibility checks.
These checks are ‘blocking’ checks, inasmuch as they cause the declaration to be rejected if the check is failed.
An example of a credibility check measure is measure type 482, which requests that a country’s border system compares the weight of a good against the submitted ‘supplementary unit’, for example number of head of cattle.
The credibility checks that were created by the European Commission are a tiny subset of what HMRC have created on CHIEF, which performs a large number of checks on data quality within declarations,
When CDS goes live, it will also feature a large number of data quality rules which will supersede these credibility checks. and, will transfer to CDS.
It is the role of HMRC in conjunction with Border Force to impose quality measures on the border systems, and therefore it is unlikely any new measures of this type will be created and it may be the case that the measures of this type that already exist will no longer be used post-Brexit
However we need to ensure we keep the existing measures in place until there is no doubt that we are fully extricated from Europe
If there is a requirement to create new credibility checks measures in the future, then it is anticipated that these will be communicated via offline methods to HMRC from the instituting source (e.g. Defra / DIT) and then entered directly into the risking module that is part of CDS, rather than being passed through the DIT Tariff Application
However, as with a number of things at the moment, the requirements of the Northern Ireland Protocol may scupper this desire to remove credibility checks entirely.

Surveillance measures


These measure types are not going to be carried forward in the UK tariff, but are used by the EU to monitor trade.
These are not to be confused with Trade Remedies-related surveillance measures, which are put in place in order to track the trade in goods that are being investigated for Trade Remedy infraction.
These trade remedy measures are also not to be carried forward.
In all cases, there are better ways of surveilling and reporting on trade. The only purpose for these measure types is to ensure that the EU can centrally impose surveillance measures across each of the 28 member states.

14.title: Trade remedies
14.content:
Trade remedies


Introduction to Trade Remedies


Anti-dumping & anti-subsidy duties


Measure types


Introduction to Trade Remedies

Trade Remedy is the name given to defensive trade instruments that can be used to protect domestic industry against illicit trade activity by overseas nations or companies, or to protect against a sudden an unexpected glut of goods entering the market.
Trade Remedies come in three flavours:
Anti-dumping duties
Anti-subsidy duties (aka countervailing duties)
Safeguards
Safeguards have some similarity to the agricultural safeguards (e.g. representative prices for chicken, the Entry Price System), in that they are not put in place to punish illicit behaviour, rather to act as a pressure valve, should international market flows suddenly change and, thus, threaten domestic industry.

Anti-dumping and anti-subsidy duties


Anti-dumping and anti-subsidy duties are quite similar, therefore should be dealt with together. Both are put in place to protect domestic industry against uncompetitive behaviour by overseas business.
Anti-dumping duties may be applied when an overseas business is found guilty of ‘dumping’ its product on a foreign market at a price which is lower than it would have been sold on its own domestic market, and that dumping has been found to cause injury to suppliers in that overseas market, who could lose market share as a result.
Anti-subsidy duties may be applied when an overseas is found to have gained an unfair advantage in international commerce through illegal state subsidies, which allow the company to market their goods at a distorted low price, again threatening the viability of international rivals.
The processes for managing through anti-dumping and anti-subsidy cases are also very similar and will be dealt with together in this guide.

Safeguard duties


Until 2018, safeguards were extremely rare. Then the current President of the United States set out on his protectionist approach to boosting US industry by applying punitive duties to goods coming into the country from abroad.
World trade is a fine balance – any drastic change in activity (pricing, demand etc) from one significant party will affect the trade flows throughout the world – this happened with steel and related metal products from 2017 onwards, when USA whacked 25% duties on imports of steel from major exporters.
The net effect of this was that suppliers of steel, which previously had a fertile market in USA had to find alternative buyers. Europe became the next market, and the knock-on impact was to damage EU suppliers’ viability.
Therefore the EU put in place, from early 2018 onwards, a set of safeguard measures to attempt to restore a pre-Trump balance of trade. These took the form of a combination of a 25% additional duty (to be charged over and above the MFN or any preference applied duty), which was then moderated by the application of quotas to certain goods that were made available to specific countries, such that the EU could take advantage of a given volume of ‘cheap’ imported products without wrecking businesses across the EU’s industrial heartlands.
Do not confuse safeguards with retaliatory duties, which display many overt similarities – see separate guide.

Relationship with the DDaT / TRA Trade Remedies Case Mgmt System


DDaT has also constructed a dedicated case management application for use by the TRA in managing a Trade Remedy case from initiation to completion.
While the subject matter is the same, there is no data link currently between this application and Tariffs.
While at the end of the investigation, the TRA would construct a document containing recommended punitive tariff duties to be forwarded to the DIT Secretary of State for a yes / no decision, this is effectively offline: a document is constructed with a management summary, leading then to a public notice which is then posted on gov.uk.
The TRA will be expected to complete a pro-forma (essentially an Excel spreadsheet) describing to the MTPO team the duties they have agreed to impose


Anti-dumping & anti-subsidy duties
Trade Remedies cases
Trade Remedies cases are rare, but when they happen, they are significant chunks of work, both for the investigating authority and, ultimately, for the Tariff Manager. As an average, in the EU, there are c. 10 new Trade Remedies cases investigated through to conclusion annually, which sounds small – but the impact on the tariff is drastic.

The TRA / TRID


While we are a part of the EU, the UK has no authority or team to investigate anti-dumping / anti-subsidy complaints: all such activity is undertaken by the relevant Trade Defence organisation within the European Commission.
When we leave, this trade defence role will be taken on by the Trade Remedies Authority (TRA). At the point of writing, the TRA has not been formally instituted: the intention had been to create an Arms’ Length Body, affiliated to but completely independent of the Department for International Trade. The legal vehicle through which the TRA was to be formed (The Trade Act) is yet to be passed, therefore the TRA exists in an intermediate state, still as part of DIT under the guise of the TRID (Trade Remedies Investigations Directorate) - the evolution into the TRA is expected in 2020.
Until the end of the Implementation period, which could be as early as Jan 1st 2021, the UK will remain as a part of the EU’s Common External Tariff and, as such, will not be able to impose its own punitive duties, however the ability to investigate cases starts on Feb 1st 2020 – we are going to begin by reviewing the duties imposed in the EU cases that we are retaining

Initiating cases


Article 5 of the WTO Anti-Dumping Agreement and article 11 of the WTO Subsidies and Countervailing Measures Agreement state that investigations can only be initiated following a written application by or on behalf of the domestic industry.
For an investigation to proceed, the companies requesting that investigation must account for more than 25% of total domestic production of the product in question
Their output must also exceed that of domestic producers that expressly oppose an investigation.
They must also provide preliminary prima facie evidence of dumping, injury and causation.
Unless these conditions are met the investigating authority cannot initiate a case, without being subject to the risk of a legal challenge by the exporter’s home country. There are no related provisions dictating how the initiation of safeguards investigations should work.
However, trade remedy investigation authorities can initiate cases without this application (ex-officio initiations), in special circumstances but there must be sufficient evidence of dumping or a subsidy, evidence of injury, and a causal link between the two.
Ex-officio initiations are possible in the EU and most other comparable countries, with the exception of New Zealand.
However, none of these countries have ‘self-initiated’ cases via their investigating authority except in exceptional circumstances.

Investigation methodology


When an investigation is initiated, WTO Agreements set out the parameters for the investigation and the evidence that should be gathered. Within these parameters, the UK Government intends that the investigation methodology should be objective and transparent when: 


establishing the level of dumping (in anti-dumping cases), 
determining the impacts of a subsidy (in anti-subsidy cases) 
identifying unexpected surges of imports (in safeguards cases) should be objective and transparent 
determining injury (or serious injury in the case of safeguards), and the causal links.


Determining measures

Provisional Measures
Provisional measures enable countries to prevent injury being caused to a domestic industry while the latter stages of a trade remedies investigation is being carried out, subject to certain conditions, as follows:
  * an investigation has been initiated and all parties have been given the opportunity to submit information and make comments,
  * the preliminary findings suggest that dumping has taken place or a subsidy exists, causing injury to a domestic industry, and
  * provisional measures are considered necessary to prevent injury while the remainder of the investigation is being conducted.
The Agreements also state that provisional measures cannot be applied before 60 days after the initiation of the investigation, and must be taken for the minimum time possible and not normally exceeding four months. In anti-dumping cases, provisional measures can be applied for up to six months where exporters representing a significant amount of the trade involved request it. In cases where a lower duty is applied than the margin of dumping these periods can be extended to six and nine months respectively.
Provisional safeguard measures can also, under article 6 of the WTO Safeguards Agreement, be applied in critical circumstances where there is evidence that an unforeseen surge in imports have caused or are threatening to cause serious injury to a domestic industry. The duration of the provisional measure in a safeguards case is not allowed to exceed 200 days. The duration of any provisional measure counts towards the total period for which the safeguard may apply.
Within the framework set out by the WTO, provisional measures can be applied at different stages in the investigations process. For example, the US applies them after they have received data from respondents in an investigation, but before that data has been verified. The EU applies them after verification of the data has taken place. There is a balance to be struck between providing early protection for the domestic industry, and setting provisional measures at the appropriate level based on sound data.
If the investigation fails to find a justifiable case for the application of trade remedy measures, the investigation is terminated and provisional duties have to be repaid. On occasion, provisional duties imposed on an exporter are lower than definitive duties. In these cases the exporter is required to top up the difference. Similarly, any duties imposed as a result of provisional safeguard measures have to be promptly refunded to the exporter if the subsequent investigation does not determine that increased imports have caused or threatened to cause serious injury to a domestic industry or were not unforeseen.
For anti-dumping cases, provisional measures may take the form of a provisional duty or a security - by cash deposit or bond - equal to no more than the amount of the anti-dumping margin provisionally estimated. For anti-subsidy cases, provisional measures may take the form of provisional countervailing duties guaranteed by cash deposits or bonds equal to no more than the amount of the provisionally calculated amount of subsidisation. For safeguards, provisional measures should take the form of tariff increases.
Concluding Trade Remedy Investigations
Once a final determination has been made in a trade remedies investigation, definitive measures can be applied. These are usually in the form of duties, undertakings, or occasionally in the form of tariff rate quotas (particularly for safeguards). These measures are applied at the border by HMRC.
Undertakings
Undertakings can be an alternative to anti-dumping duties or countervailing measures (definitive or provisional).  In the case of dumped imports, these are generally price undertakings, whereby an exporter enters into a voluntary agreement to revise the export price of their product or cease exporting at dumped prices so as to eliminate the injury caused. In the case of subsidised imports, an exporter or the exporter’s government enters into a voluntary agreement to: a) eliminate or limit the subsidy or take other measures concerning its effects; or b) raise the export price of their product so as to eliminate the injury caused.  Undertakings do not apply in relation to safeguards. 
Where undertakings are used, WTO rules set out procedures to follow.  Undertakings may only be offered or sought after a preliminary affirmative determination of dumping and injury caused.  When an undertaking is accepted, investigation proceedings may be terminated unless either the exporter (in anti-dumping cases) or exporter’s Government (in subsidies cases) want the investigation completed or if the investigating authority so decides.  If a negative determination of dumping or injury is subsequently made, the undertaking normally lapses.  If an affirmative determination is made, the undertaking remains in force.
There are no tariff measures that are placed as a result of undertakings
Reviewing cases
The decision to impose trade remedy measures has significant repercussions, both for the exporting industries whose business models will be directly impacted by the measures imposed, and for domestic industries and other interested parties within the receiving country. It is important, therefore, that a mechanism exists to review the measures in place, and that this mechanism is clear, transparent and effective, and allows measures only to continue as long as they are necessary.
Article 11 of WTO Anti-Dumping Agreement contains provisions relating to the duration and the review of measures. In the case  of dumping and subsidy, measures should remain in force no longer than is necessary to counteract the injury caused, and cannot be in force for longer than 5 years without being reviewed. Any review should normally be concluded within 12 months. In the case of safeguards, if the duration of the measure exceeds three years, then it should be reviewed not later than at the mid-point of the measure.  . Any measures in place for over 1 year should be progressively liberalised and no measures should be in place for more than 8 years in total.
In order to abide by these WTO requirements, the UK Government intends to create a trade remedies review process which is consistent with the approach to new investigations.
Monitoring cases
2.7.1   Circumvention & Absorption
Circumvention and absorption both refer to practices which are designed to avoid anti-dumping or anti-subsidy duties and, if left unchecked, will undermine the effect of trade remedy measures.
‘Circumvention’ refers to a process through which an exporter subject to anti-dumping or countervailing measure duties, or an importer liable to pay the duty, attempts to evade that duty through particular practices. In some instances these practices will be fraudulent activities for which there are separate HMRC enforcement provisions. Circumvention can take several forms including slight modifications of the product, transhipment via a third country, or assembly of the product in either a third country or the importing country with minimal value added.
Duties are said to be ‘absorbed’ when, after anti-dumping or countervailing duties have been imposed, export prices decrease or the resale prices of the imported goods do not increase sufficiently, resulting in the measures not having the expected effect of restoring competitive prices.
The WTO Anti-Dumping and Subsidies and Countervailing Measures Agreements make no specific provision for circumvention or absorption reviews.  Most other countries’ trade remedies systems specify processes for reviewing cases and extending the anti-dumping measures as appropriate to tackle circumvention. For absorption, different trade remedies systems tackle the problem in different ways depending on the way in which duties are collected at the border of the country or region in question.
The UK Government intends to create an efficient and effective trade remedies framework should be robust enough to tackle these sorts of practices, which undermine the intended effect of the measures.
Migrating cases


As per the earlier note on migrating cases, for an investigation to proceed, the companies requesting that investigation must account for more than 25% of total domestic production of the product in question. Their output must also exceed that of domestic producers that expressly oppose an investigation.
These criteria also apply when considering the migration of trade remedy cases from the EU to the UK. At the end of the implementation period, we will only transition the cases that meet these thresholds and which are seen to be in the public interest to maintain.
