Debatable     As above


ME50
The combination measurement unit + measurement unit   qualifier must exist.
Required     The relationship between a measurement_unit and any   qualifer that can be used against that measurement unit is defined in the   table “measurements” – this needs to be observed fully or CDS will generate   an error. Measurements have start and end dates against them, and these also   need to be observed.

Additional codes


Introduction to additional codes


Type 2 - Preference codes


Type 3 – P & R codes


Type 4 – Restriction codes


Type 7 - Meursing codes


Type 8, A, B, C – Anti-subsidy / anti-dumping codes




Screen designs


Key user needs – additional codes


Key business rules – additional codes


Introduction to additional codesWhat is an additional code?


As detailed in the training manual on goods nomenclature (commodity codes), in most cases, the 10 digits of the EU commodity code hierarchy are fully sufficient to identify the product that is being traded.
However, there are certain scenarios where the 10-digits are not enough and an additional 4 digits are required (and sometimes 8) to communicate sufficient information to describe the trade.
This is where additional codes come in.




Additional codes may be appended to a commodity code to make the number of (effective) digits up to 14, or possibly 18.
Importantly though, there is no such thing as a 14-digit commodity code: commodity codes can be augmented by additional codes, but the two entities are managed completely separately: a single additional code can and usually is appended to multiple commodity codes through the medium of measures; similarly a single commodity code can have an association with multiple additional codes, again through measures applied to a given combination of commodity and additional code.

What are additional codes used for?


Additional codes are now used to manage:


Meursing codes – for sugar, flour and milk duties associated with complex agricultural products
Anti-dumping & anti-subsidy duties – to identify the specific company to which a punitive measure is attached
Pharma products – to identify that the end use of an imported good is for pharmaceutical purposes, and therefore attracts a reduced duty
Differentiating product states / uses / origins (e.g. waste chemicals, underwear [!])
Route of ingress – to identify the route goods (wheat & other cereals) take into EU and to apply different tariff or regulatory treatment
Works of art – to identify items stolen from Syria and Iraq as a result of wartime activity

Each of the above uses are discussed in detail on the following slides.
Additional codes are made up of 4 digits, which are split into two parts:


Structure of additional codes and additional code types


Much like certificates and footnotes, additional codes are made up of a type and then a specific ID, which, when concatenated, form the unique ID of the additional code. .
For example, the additional code C233 is constructed of a type © and a specific footnote ID (233) – the entire additional code is known as C233.
The numeric IDs, running from 001 to 999 can be reused across multiple additional code type IDs.
While the schema allows for us to use alphanumeric digits for additional codes, not just numeric, these are almost never used and never by the EU – there are 7 national additional codes that are used by HMRC for VAT and excise.
The use of the alphanumeric codes may be of great importance to the Northern Ireland protocol, subject to the way in which the solution progresses.
Additional code type IDs are always single alphabetical characters (those set by the EU) or single numeric characters (set as national additional code by the UK).

      Type 7 - Meursing codes

Introduced in 1988 by the European Commission. Traders hate them, but we have to keep Meursing classifications or change our WTO commitments.
They apply to bakery and confectionery products, etc. classed as “composite agrigoods”. Meursing allows extra set of import duties to be charged depending on how much of 4 agricultural ingredients are used to make the product: milk fat, milk proteins, starch or glucose, or various forms of sugar.
The result used to be tens of thousands of categories of composite agrigoods for the purposes of charging import duties. To find the specific ‘recipe’ and the duties applicable, you look it up in the Meursing table (right).
Executed in the tariff as a combination of primary measures, such as tariff preferences, with complex duty expression combinations, which are then expanded when the trader select the ‘additional code’ for the specific ‘recipe’ of their product.
The best description of Meursing codes and their use is drawn up by Trade expert Peter Unghpakorn on his trade beta blog: https://tradebetablog.wordpress.com/2016/08/18/eu-tariff-biscuit-annex1/



Future of Meursing codes


The Meursing code is a staple of EU agrifood trade.
The UK policy however is to abandon Meursing codes as an agricultural policy, due to the fact that it is universally disliked by trade and policy (Defra) alike – the tax-raising reasons for it having come into existence in the first place are not UK policy.
However, as with much of the Northern Ireland protocol, there are additional implications for UK government and Northern Ireland traders with NI remaining in a special relationship with the EU’s Customs Union.
Initial thoughts are that the impact of the NI protocol will not be felt for GB traders, but NI traders will continue to need to apply Meursing codes to imports of specific types if the good is considered to be at risk of being further transported to the EU.
At the very least, this requires DIT policy and DDaT to retain some knowledge of the Meursing challenge, even if the majority of the UK will not be subject to the controls

Application of a Meursing code in detail – Waffles and wafers


Let’s take “waffles and wafers - with a water content exceeding 10% by weight”, commodity code 1905320500.

The third country duty reads as follows:9.00% + EA MAX 20.7% + ADFM
This is a complex compound duty involving both a ceiling and a pair of Meursing-related placeholders. These placeholders come in three forms, which, in the EU are labelled:
EA – Agricultural component 
ADFM – Additional duty on flour
ADSZ – Additional duty on sugar (not shown here, but the principle applies)
The labels are based on French and German abbreviations (élément agricole, farine / mehl; sucre / Zucker)
The next section shows the breakdown – and what traders have to do


Unpicking complex agricultural duties


The waffle duty 9.00% + EA MAX 20.7% + ADFM is made up of 4 measure components – please review the training manual on measure components for a detailed view of these.

The first thing to notice is that the Meursing placeholders have no duties assigned to them – it is not possible to assign duty amounts to these measure components; they operate as placeholders that are filled in only when traders declare the content of the various delicious ingredients.
The trader goes to (for example) the gov.uk URL below, enters the component %ages and then is eventually presented with a 4-digit code, such as 7364.
Duties are then assigned specifically against the Meursing additional code 7364, totally independent of the hundreds of commodities that are subject to them – this is unique in the tariff database, where duties are usually against combinations of commodity codes and additional codes - not with Meursings.


https://www.gov.uk/additional-commodity-code
Implications for Tariffs project


Although it is theoretically possible that the UK will need to manage Meursing additional codes and their associated duties in the future, it is highly unlikely
Recommendation would be that no interface functionality is constructed to allow for managing Meursing codes themselves, as it is hugely complex.
Theoretically, if we wanted to just change the duties associated with the Meursing additional codes, this is possible: it is a matter of assigning duties direct to an additional code, rather than to a combination of commodity codes and additional codes.

Meursing table and the reduction indicator


There is one Meursing table but multiple layers of tariffs assigned against it
The “reduction indicator” is assigned to the tariff measure on the commodity code and to the duty assigned to the additional code. The border system picks the indicator that matches to select the right duty.
In use with multiple preferential agreements that reference composite agrigoods.
Japan goes to town on the usage of reduction indicators, forcing the EU to change its Taric schema to accommodate another three reduction tables.
By the end of the implementation period, be aware of two facts:
we will have done away with the concept of Meursing codes in the UK, therefore the reduction indicator will be irrelevant
we will not have a trade agreement with Japan
BUT:
we will need to honour the NI protocol, meaning Meursings will apply to imports of at risk goods from RoW and GB to NI, meaning DIT and DDaT need to continue to be aware of their presence.


Type 8, A, B, C – Anti-subsidy / anti-dumping codesA Trade Remedy is explained elsewhere, but the important thing to note is that, for the two types of trade remedy that are by some distance the most abundant, Anti-dumping duties and Anti-subsidy duties, the punitive import duties are set against specific exporting companies that are deemed to have acted unlawfully, not against entire countries.
Essentially, a company is proven to have been dumping1 its goods on an overseas market (e.g. the European Union or the United Kingdom), or to have been receiving unlawful state subsidy to undercut international competitors, and this activity is found to have been damaging businesses in those overseas nations. In such cases, the nation or bloc’s Trade Remedies body, such as our own Trade Remedies Authority, is entitled to investigate and impose punitive duties specifically against the companies that have been proven to have acted unlawfully.
In the case of Trade Remedies, the 4-digit additional code is set to represent the company from which the good is imported, or in some cases, a multitude of companies that have been found guilty of the same infraction.


By way of example:
Code C316 refers to Bengang Steel Plates Co., Ltd (Benxi, Liaoning)
Code C333 refers to all of:
* Aeolus Tyre Co., Ltd;
* Aeolus Tyre (Taiyuan) Co., Ltd;
* Qingdao Yellow Sea Rubber Co., Ltd;
* Pirelli Tyre Co., Ltd
To create a punitive trade remedy duty against a the import of “flat rolled steel” from “Bengang Steel Plates”, you assign a 552 measure against commodity code 7225990092 and additional code C316.

When the European Commission first set up the Taric database to cater for all trade eventualities, they were somewhat guilty of short-sightedness when it came to Trade Remedies.
They set up the additional type code ‘8’ in 1972 to deal with all future companies implicated in Trade Remedy cases. To be fair, this lasted until 1999, when the 1,000 possible permutations within the ‘8 ‘ type code (000 to 999) were exhausted. They then moved on to using ‘A’. In 2013, they moved on to ‘B’ and in ‘2015’ to ‘C’. By 2019, type ‘C’ was already half used up, so the expectation would be that they will move on to another additional code type within the next 2 years.
‘D’ is already used for dual use codes, albeit it is currently dormant.
In preparing for the multiple abortive stabs at EU Exit, the project team has (via scripts) created an additional set of additional code types (‘E’ and ‘F’) to cater for the inevitable expansion and deviation.
Additional codes, according to the Taric schema may be alphabetical, as well as numeric – alpha characters have never been used by the EU, but there is no reason why we could not use them in the future in the UK.


Additional codes used in Trade Remedies measures are essentially meaningless beyond Tariff – there is literally no reference against any international database of companies, nor any attempt to make the data set atomic and ‘cleansed’
You are likely to find multiple instances of the same company cropping up in the database on multiple occasions.
Be careful about the shenanigans that companies get up to evade punitive duties – most often by setting up subsidiaries in overseas nations with similar names: these are not the same company, nor the same additional code, but they may have very similar company names.

Additional codes cannot be applied universally …
There is an additional many to many table within the tariff database that determines which additional code types can be used against which measure types. Currently there are 74 permutations of additional codes against measure types: there is little surprising about the alignment – e.g. you can only assign additional codes of type 8, A, B or C to measure types that are associated with Trade Remedies.

22.title: Quota suspensions
22.content:
Quota suspensions


Managing suspension periods on TAP


Key user needs


Key business rules


Background to Quotas


A quota provides an opportunity for an importer to import goods at a rate that is lower than the prevailing MFN (or preferential rate) until the specified volume of goods has run out (or exhausted).
Once the volume has exhausted, the quota is no longer available and the out-of-quota-rate is then payable.
A quota can be managed via two regimes, as follows: First Come First Served (FCFS) and Licensed.




Quota suspensions are applicable only to First Come First Serve quotas

What are quota suspensions?


Quota suspensions are functions that are enabled in legal text to allow for First Come First Serve quotas to be made effectively unavailable to traders for a given period of time, for a number of reasons – these reasons are typically written into the initial legal text, such that there is no requirement to legislate to bring in the suspension.
Some typical reasons are as follows:


The administrative costs of running the quota mean that there is no value in doing so while the MFN rate is equal to or lower than the in-quota rate – for example, the image to the below is a fragment of EU regulation “2016/1219, amending Council Regulation (EC) No 499/96 as regards Union tariff quotas for certain fish and fishery products originating in Iceland” – the footnote explains why the quota is suspended from 15 Feb to 15 June.
e.g. for fishing quotas, a quota is applicable only while overall catch volumes do not exceed a given amount.



Logical model of a quota suspension



Using the herrings example from the previous page, quota 09.0792 runs annually from January 1st to December 31st and is applied to commodity code 0303510000.
The MFN is 15.00% all year round, except for the period between Feb 15th and June 15th, where it is 0.00% (tariff free)
The EU has chosen to suspend the quota for the period where the MFN is zero, as there is no value in running a quota when there is no material gain to be made for the trader in applying for quota usage during that period.

When is a quota not a quota?
A quota suspension can be thought of as an antidote to a quota; a nullification of its effects; during the period of the suspension, it is as if the quota is not there; a trader cannot request an allocation against that quota and it is invisible on the Trade Tariff Service, as follows:
For 1st July 2019, after the suspension, the quota is visible https://www.trade-tariff.service.gov.uk/commodities/0303510010?currency=EUR&day=1&month=7&year=2019#import

For 1st March, during the suspension, the quota is hiddenhttps://www.trade-tariff.service.gov.uk/commodities/0303510010?currency=EUR&day=1&month=7&year=2019#import
It is important to note however that there a many ways to skin a cat: in this example, the EU has also made the quota measures last from 16th June to 14th Feb and not all year long.
Simplified quotas data model (as applies to suspension periods)

A quota order number is made up of many quota definition periods
When setting up quotas, it’s important to understand that a single quota order number record is made up of many definition periods: these periods may be of any length (no longer than a year, with the most typical lengths being annual and quarterly, as well as a number of custom periods, especially re: agricultural goods & seasonal marketing periods).

Quota suspension data object in detail
The quota suspension object is not one of the more complex objects in the database: there are few fields, in fact there are only three that you need to actively define.


        
          
Field
Description


quota_suspension_period_sid
Unique   identifier, automatically generated by the application when a new suspension   period is created – you do no create this yourself


quota_definition_sid
The   quota definition to which the suspension is to be attached – you do not need   to enter the ID of the definition: you select it from a list (as will be   demonstrated)


suspension_start_date
The   start date of the suspension blocking period – i.e. 00:00 at the start of the   chosen day


suspension_end_date
The   end date of the suspension blocking period – i.e. 00:00 at the end of the   chosen day


description
An   optional field, up to 500 characters in length, that helps to define the   suspension and the reasons for it: the EU has been deeply unhelpful /   non-descriptive in its suspension descriptions and we may choose to be more   expressive post-EU Exit


        
      
A suspension period must fit within a definition period
The critical point is that a quota suspension is defined against a quota definition period: the suspension period MUST NOT straddle the boundary of the definition – in the rare occasion you need to straddle a boundary, create 2 suspension

Dates on TAP


A reminder from the main training manual that there is a peculiarity that should be surfaced with regard to dates on TAP.
Most objects on the database are bookended by start dates and end dates.
For measures, quota definitions, geographical areas and most other data objects, these dates are referred to in the database as “validity start and end dates”.
Quota suspensions periods and blocking periods are also bookended, but they break the otherwise universal rule in terms of naming fields, choosing instead:


suspension_start_date and suspension_end_date
blocking_start_date and blocking_end_date

For all of these date ranges, the same rules apply, namely:


we work on dates and not times: a single day is the smallest unit of time
for start dates, the actual ‘start’ is defined as being 00:00 at the start of the day
for end dates, the actual ‘end’ is defined as being 00:00 at the end of the day
therefore, if the start and end dates of a given object are identical, this equates to a whole 24 hours and not to 0 hours
THIS CANNOT BE STRESSED ENOUGH, and is critical to the use of suspension periods.

Quota blocking


Managing blocking periods on TAP


Key user needs


Key business rules




Please read the discussion on blocking quotas before reading this … the introduction to quotas is useful and the concepts are very similar
As with suspensions, quota blocking periods are applicable only to First Come First Serve quotas

Why are quotas blocked?


Quota blocks are placed on quotas for a limited period of time to prevent allocations from being taken.
Unlike suspensions, which effectively invalidate a quota (as if it does not exist and is suspended in law), all a blocking period does is to prevent allocations from being made: it does not prevent declarations from being made against a quota: it just postpones any allocation decision.
A quota blocking period usually coincides with the start of a definition period, though not always; for instance, a common blocking reason is to protect the re-opening of a quota after significant returns
This effect of a quota blocking period is to give HMRC an opportunity to assess the demand for a quota and potentially give an opportunity for them to make subjective decisions on allocations, e.g. to prevent a single large business from using up an entire allocation before smaller players have got their act together.
277 of the 455 blocking periods created in 2019 coincided with the start of definition period.
In these cases, it is most likely that the block will last c. 2 or 3 weeks


Quota blocking reasons
Unlike with suspensions, where the Tariff Manager can only enter descriptive text to describe a suspension period, blocking periods include a field which describe the reason for the blocking period.

      Options 1 and 3 are the most common – option 1 actually seems more by design that just accidental late publication
Logical model of a quota blocking period

A quota starts on Jan 1st and runs throughout the year
The decision is taken to place a block on the quota for the first 15 days, to allow HMRC to make an assessment on potential usage of the quota, by taking allocation requests, but not actually allocating / decrementing the opening balance
This gives smaller traders and new entrants an opportunity to take advantage of the reduced rate

Introduction to footnotesStructure of footnotes & footnote types


Much like certificates and additional codes, footnotes are made up of a type and then a specific ID, which, when concatenated, form the unique ID of the footnote.
For example, the footnote CD491 is constructed of a type (CD) and a specific footnote ID (491) – the entire footnote is known as CD491.
The numeric IDs, running from 001 to 999 can be reused across multiple footnote type IDs
In actual fact, footnote IDs may be either 3 or 5 digits long according to the XSD – all footnotes to date have been 3 digits long and while there is no clear reason to change, as footnotes are not so voluminous that the numbers are running out in many of the current database’s footnote type, there is benefit in considering a move to 5 digits (see below)
Footnote type IDs are either 2 alphabetical characters (those set by the EU) or 2 numeric characters (set as national footnotes by the UK). As with the footnote ID, there is additional redundancy here – the data schema gives an opportunity to use 3 digit footnote ID types – there should be no reason to adopt these.

Footnotes are the last thing to be considered in a migration, as they are informational but not operational – the tariff will still function if the footnotes are omitted.
The only exception to this rule has been the ECJU, which has been very keen to create footnotes that explain the requirement with regard to export controlled goods (such as dual use, goods for torture or sanctioned countries)

Introduction to measure conditions

Not all measures apply in all circumstances – approximately half of all the measures on the EU database are usable by traders only under certain conditions – for example, the presentation of a document.
The screen grab to the right (top) show ‘bison carcasses’ on the UK Trade Tariff Service.

Going back to the list of condition codes, there are a number of condition codes which make reference to a minimum or maximum import price, otherwise known as a reference price (or trigger price). These are highlighted in blue to the left.
The most frequent & volatile example of this in the EU tariff is condition type V – this is used to manage the Entry Price System (detailed later).

Condition code B means “Presentation of a certificate/licence/document” and is common to both conditions.
There is no trigger price (hence 4 * null fields across both conditions).
Action codes are complementary (27 and 7) – the 27 is the positive and the 7 is the negative.
The certificate required to effect the positive action is Y085

AND / OR logic for condition codes


Conditions are grouped together according to their condition code.
Within that group, the individual conditions are grouped together in an OR relationship, for example, in the conditions associated with the B condition code to the right, only one of the three noted goods needs to be provided, however it must be provided alongside one of the other conditions from block E being met (provision of a document or the weight of the imported good being below 2kg).
In this way, an additional tier is added to the logical condition model via the condition code grouping.



Volumes of conditions


Do not underestimate the complexity of measure conditions – there are up to 26 conditions on measures, as per the example here on commodity code 0308110000 (Aquatic invertebrates other than crustaceans and molluscs, live, fresh, chilled, frozen, dried, salted or in brine; smoked aquatic invertebrates other than crustaceans and molluscs, whether or not cooked before or during the smoking process; flours, meals and pellets of aquatic invertebrates other than crustaceans and molluscs, fit for human consumption)against the EU (measure_sid 3566626)
In this case, the conditions are aligned against 2 condition codes:


within condition code B and E respectively, any of the positive conditions will result in an acceptance of the trade.
at least one condition needs to be fulfilled within each of the two condition code groups.

The intellectual knowledge of certification is a huge challenge in DIT, Defra and HMG as a whole - over the implementation period, significant effort in DIT and Defra should be expended in looking to understand certification.


Detailed overview of condition codesCondition code A



This condition code is used to modify the circumstances of an anti-dumping or anti-subsidy duty depending on the conditions stated.
There are three scenarios in which this condition code is used, two of which have 2 related (and opposite action codes)


Scenario 1 – apply conditional duties depending on supply of document
Scenario 2 – determine if the trade can go ahead
Scenario 3 - determining applicability of exemption/reduction of the anti-dumping duty


Scenario 1 – apply conditional duties depending on supply of document


This is by far the most common application of conditional duties for trade remedy-related measures
The applicable duty can be conditional on the supply of a document: if the document is supplied then the duty is reduced
This scenario is executed by:


setting multiple (usually two) measure conditions with condition code A
then assigning action code 01, which states ”Apply the amount of the action”
and to each condition then assigning an applicable duty

The documents used in the EU, presumably to be followed in the UK are as follows:


D005 - Commercial invoice within the framework of undertakings
D008 - Invoice with a signed declaration
D017 - Commercial invoice within the framework of undertakings and Export Undertaking Certificate
D018 - Invoice for transactions which are not exempted from countervailing/anti-dumping duties


Scenario 2 – determine if the trade can go ahead at all


Features a pair of action codes which are always supplied together and are opposites of each other


08 - Declared subheading not allowed
The trade will be rejected in CDS
This is always associated with no document being specified, therefore not presented with the trade
28 - Declared subheading allowed
This is always associated with a document being specified, therefore presented with the trade and hence, the trade being permitted

There is only one certificate that has been used in conjunction with this condition code / action code permutation


D020 - Commercial invoice and mill certificate as defined in Regulation 2015/1953

This scenario is not currently in use, but it has been used in the past

Scenario 3 – determining applicability of exemption/reduction of the anti-dumping duty


As with scenario 2, this features a pair of conditions with complementing action codes that are always found together
Though not completely defunct, this is used only three times in current measures by the EU
The two action codes are:


34 - Apply exemption/reduction of the anti-dumping duty
14 - The exemption/reduction of the anti-dumping duty is not applicable

This basically means that the antidumping duty will be waived entirely or reduced according to the legislation. There are no conditional duties set however, therefore it is not 100% clear where the duty calculation will get its raw data from
The conditions should be applied in the sequence 34 then 14, i.e. positive followed by negative
There is only one current certificate in use that is used with this condition code / action code combination


D008 - Invoice with a signed declaration




Conditions B, C and H are identical in meaning
C and H are used when multiple condition sets using the same mechanic need to be applied to the same measure.

Condition codes B, C & H



Codes B, C and H require a certificate or other document to be presented in order for the requirement to be fulfilled.
Condition codes C & H are identical to condition code B, and there is no overt reason as to why C / H might be used instead of B – they are however sometimes used alongside code B.
Commodity code 8418690091 provides the answer as to why there are two types of condition that are ostensibly identical, i.e. there is a desire to apply multiple conditions sets to the same measure (in this case Import control of fluorinated greenhouse gases).
If just B had been used, it would not have been possible to apply the AND logic of the two condition groups.
H is used only 41 times (Jan 2020); C is used c. 5,000 times whereas B is vastly more prevalent (c. 24,000 occurrences).


Condition code E



This condition code is a combination of a quantitative restriction plus a documentation requirement, i.e. a trade will be allowed provided the volume of goods is lower than the defined threshold weight (or other unit), or a document is provided that permits the trade in a larger volume of goods.
The criteria that define these two conditions are set in the measure condition data.


Condition code I



These condition codes are currently used uniquely with measure types 751 and 755 (import and export control of waste)
They are functionally identical to condition code E (see above).
Type I is only ever used in conjunction with type E to present a send condition set of the same type, never on its own


Condition code F



These conditions allow duties to be charged against imported goods subject to Trade Remedies (Anti dumping or anti subsidy duties) that are dependent upon the unit price of the import.
This is significantly less commonly used than condition code A, which is also used to apply conditional logic to the trade of a good subject to an AD / AS duty, but remains an option for the TRA: there are 119 such conditions against 17,000 + of type A.
In the example to the right on measure 3571830 on commodity 2933610000 (melamine), there are two F-type conditions, which are dependent on the import price: the duties are set accordingly.
What these conditions say is:


if the goods is imported at a price of higher than €1153 per tonne, then apply zero additional punitive duty (condition 1)
BUT if the import of the good is at a lower price, apply the difference between the import price and the punitive duty

This essentially sets a minimum import 


Condition code L



This is currently used only 30 times and is always applied to measures of type 652 - Additional duty based on cif price
This measure type is used in managing a complex agricultural duty called “Representative prices for chicken”, which in the EU tariff is applied to certain poultry products that are being traded from Argentina, Brazil, Chile and Thailand – the most aggressive of chicken traders.
The UK is not going to be taking on this policy, unless plans change between now and the end of 2020.
The policy is far too complex to describe here, but is described in detail in the general training manual.

*Condition code M *



Condition code M is used in two circumstances:


The first circumstance is the in managing EU supplied credibility checks of type:
430 Control of particulars of the declaration (suspicious value/net weight or value/supplementary unit)
483 Declaration of subheading submitted to restrictions (value)

A credibility check is a mechanism that is employed in a border system to attempt to reduce errors in declarations by enforcing a check on (for example) the weight versus item count ratio of a declaration.
430 and 483 are measures (along with 431) that are used by the EU to ensure that discrepancies are avoided.
The EU provides these across the whole of the EU because they are trying to ensure consistency and reduce errors (that they have to fix for all 28 member states).
After EU Exit, the UK will provide its own credibility checks – the EU’s measures will be terminated
In reality, the EU’s credibility checks are a small subset of the overall number of checks that are carried out. CHIEF and CDS are replete with many UK-specific credibility checks as well. In the future, these will all be managed by HMRC, not by DIT MTPO, therefore are out of scope for DIT (albeit there is nothing to prevent TAP from creating these).
The second circumstance will continue after EU Exit, as it deals with Trade Remedies. The existing conditions of this type are against measure type ID 552 Definitive anti-dumping duty, but there is no reason why this would not also be assigned to measure types 551, 553 and 554.
This follows a similar pattern to other threshold-based commodities previously noted
There are currently (Jan 2020) 84 instances of condition code M.
In the examples to the right, there are two conditions which behave more or less the same as condition type F, where the applicable punitive duty is dependent the declared price [F depends on net free at frontier price before duty].


Condition code Q



Condition type Q is used in all cases where a measure is put in place to represent a licensed quota. And in all cases it refers to the single license Y100 (Special entries on the import licence AGRIM). It is used in measures of type:


122  Non preferential tariff quota
123  Non preferential tariff quota under end-use
142  Tariff preference
143  Preferential tariff quota

It is only used for licensed quotas; it is never used for FCFS quotas.


Condition code R



As per scenario 1 for condition code M, this is used to apply conditions to credibility checks to ensure that the weight ‘looks right’ against the number of declared goods. The supplementary unit identifies what additional unit beyond the KGM weight must be supplied by the trader on declaring their import.
Again, as per condition code M, the UK will be abandoning the practise of managing credibility checks in the Taric file after EU Exit.

Condition code U



As per scenario 1 for condition codes M & R, this is used to apply conditions to credibility checks to ensure that the declared value ‘looks right’ against the number of declared goods.
The supplementary unit identifies what additional unit beyond the KGM weight must be supplied by the trader on declaring their import.
As per condition codes M & R, the UK will be abandoning the practise of managing credibility checks in the Taric file after EU Exit.

Condition code V – The Entry price System


The Entry Price System (EPS) is a complex mechanism to apply tiered duties to 31 agricultural products, primarily fruit.
The EPS is described in detail elsewhere, so this page will not go into that much detail, especially as the UK will be abandoning the Entry Price System. It supports growers of (primarily) citrus fruits in Southern Europe: the UK’s less sunny climes do not lend themselves to industrial-scale citriculture.




The screen above is captured from the third country duty for cherry tomatoes – this shows the EPS in action.
The duties that are applicable depend on the import price: the cheaper the import, the more expensive the duty
The purpose of this is to protect domestic growers in s. Europe from influxes of very cheap goods

Condition code V

The data for EPS-related measures is as per the example to the right – just one row (marquee below).

In the example above, each row is a price threshold: if the import price falls below a given threshold, then the duty from the row below is charged.

This is, as its name suggests a catch all that can be used to manage effectively any condition not specifically covered by the other condition codes. In practice, this seems to have been used in the past by the EU for managing certificates, much in the vein of conditions with code B, C or H. But the real reason for using this is for non-specific conditions that are not associated with a specific document.
These miscellaneous conditions are linked to in much the same way that certificates are referenced, using the certificate type code and certificate code fields. Here are a few examples of conditions that are referenced by condition code Y. None of these are documents per se: they reference properties of goods or activities undertaken by traders outside of the core declaration flow.
For example:
* Y019  Request for preferential treatment for Iceland
* Y021  Request for EEA preferential treatment
* Y034  Derogation from export prohibition by virtue of Article 4.1 of Council Regulation (EU) 2017/1509
* Y037  Goods exempted from the prohibition – biathlon equipment
None of the conditions linked to via the condition code ‘Y’ utilise the price threshold fields.
Condition code Z

Condition code Z is used solely on national P & R measures currently, though it is by no means a stipulation that this has to be so. Indeed, all the national P & R will become homogenised with the measures inherited from the EU after EU Exit – though the management of measures to support the NI Protocol may influence the specific approach.
These are the measure types where Z is used:


ATT   Attestation Document (horticulture and potatoes)
CEX   DCMS Open General Export Licence
COE   Home Office Controlled Drugs (export)
COI   HMI Conformity Certificate (fruit and veg) issued in UK
EQC   Certificate of Conformity
HOP   Home Office pre-cursor chemical authorisation
PRE   Home Office Pre-cursor chemicals
PRT   Home Office Controlled Drugs (import)

There is no reason why this condition code should be used in preference to B, C or H. Indeed there are occasions where the Z type is used, but only one positive condition is included, which seems to make the condition type pretty redundant (e.g. with EQC measures).
The advice to tariff managers would be to always use condition code B, then C then H before resorting to Z.

Quota associations


Key data fields for associations


Key examples - Equivalence associations (EQ)


Key examples - Normal associations (NM)


Managing quota associations in TAP


Key user needs – quota associations


Key business rules – quota associations


What are quota associations?


A quota association is used as a mechanism in Taric to link together quotas in such a way that the drawing down on that quota by a trader will then have an impact on another.
The detail of the trade instruments that necessitate and make use of this function are described in detail below.
The quota association links together two or more quotas’ quota definitions, which are time-bound periods, often of exactly one year, but sometimes shorter.
The association defines the link between one and only one main quota and one or more sub quotas. These are sometimes referred to respectively as parent and child quotas, though main and sub are the traditional Taric terms.
There are currently 28 main quotas that are linked to sub quotas via their definitions.


Where are quota associations used?
In the EU tariff, there are a number of key product areas where quota associations are used (or potentially could be used if such policy were adopted):
How we choose to adopt these in the UK tariff will depend on the emerging UK trade policy, for example there are a number of quota associations that are:


part of trade agreements that we are yet to transition or
have been provisionally written out of the UK equivalent.

These instances are discussed in detail on subsequent pages.

Live from Day One


Lamb, sheep and goat meat (WTO quota)
Beef (WTO quota)
Orange juice (Israel)


Live from Day One in theory


Steel (safeguards)*
Clothing (C. America quota of quotas)**


Agreements not yet transitioned


Bison meat (Canada)
Eggs and egg albumin (Mexico)


No longer required


Tomatoes (Morocco)


Key data fields for associationsQuota associations – key data fields
The data model, if not the underlying concepts for quota associations, is simple.

The key fields are defined in the box surrounded by the red dashed marquee in the diagram above.


an association links to a single main (parent) quota definition and a single sub (child) definition: these definitions define the quota order number, which is a property of the definition as well as the time extent: the association will last as long as the definitions. In most cases, the definitions of main and sub quota are equally long, however Moroccan tomatoes is the exception: while the complex Moroccan tomato quota will not be carried forward into the UK tariff, it deserves and receives some explanation in this training pack.
an association then has a relation type, defined below, and a coefficient, also explained below.

2 relation types: EQ and NM
There are two relation type values that are used to define quota associations: EQ (equivalent to main quota and NM normal). The two relation types define the two main uses of quota associations.
Quota associations are used:


to provide the opportunity to spread a quota balance across multiple order numbers and to apply a weighting to the weight or volume of the individual products (relation type EQ). The weighting is defined in the corresponding coefficient field
to apply a maximum quota volume to subsidiary products (or periods) within a parent group’s volume (relation type NM)
to allow goods to be traded evenly across multiple in-year definition periods and for balances to be transferred into a future period.
The TARIC3 IDS Elements guide document (essential reading) describes the possible relation types as per the screen grab to below.




These different types were first introduced in 2010. The following rules apply:


the value assigned to the coefficient field is always 1.00 where the relation type is “NM”.
the values assigned to the coefficient field is always something other than 1.00 where the relation type is “EQ”.

Therefore, EQ is used to relate quota order numbers where volume or weight is to be interpreted differently via a simple co-efficient.
NM is used where weight or volume is the same across each related definition, however a maximum weight / volume is applied to specific commodity codes in the sub-quota, or in the case of beef WTO quotas, to allow balance to be shared equitably across an entire year (see below).

Key examples - Equivalence associations (EQ)Sheep and goat meat – WTO quota



This is the poster boy for quota associations – the most crucial for trade of the remaining associations, given the emotional importance of the commodities involved and the number of countries impacted.
The details of the trade in sheep and goat meat are set out in the EU’s Regulation 1354 of 2011 and subsequent documents which cover the opening annual WTO Union tariff quotas for sheepmeat and goatmeat – the mechanism is copied into the UK tariff.
The reason why equivalence associations are used in this set of quotas is that there are three types of products to be traded (each represented by multiple commodities) whose imports are to be treated different, depending on what product they are
It is considered that 1kg of meat off the bone is to count less than 1kg of meat on the bone when determining quota allocations.
In the EU, this covers imports from Greenland, Argentina, Australia, Chile, Faroe Islands, Iceland, Norway, New Zealand, Turkey, Uruguay, WTO Member states and Erga Omnes.
In the UK, additional countries will be added to this list dependent on whether the trade deals with those countries have gone through, e.g. Bosnia-Herzegovina.
Please be aware also of Chile, where the volumes are shared with a preferential quota.




Page 3 of the noted regulation shows the effect and implementation of quota associations (EQ type).
The red marquee to the left shows the details of this specific sheep and goat meat quota for New Zealand (the same applies to other countries).
The EU is allowed to import 228,254 tonnes of meat from New Zealand annually. The notes above the final column are instrumental – “in tonnes of carcase weight equivalent” illustrates there is a calculation to undertake for goods of various different types in order to determine “what constitutes a tonne”.
In this case bone-in carcases are counted as 1 tonne, boneless mutton / sheep counts as 1.81 tonnes and boneless lamb counts as 1.67 tonnes. These values are reflected in the coefficients on the printed regulation and also in the quota associations table in the database (orange marquee). This setup is echoed with Bison meat (Canada).


Preferential beef quotas


There are also beef quotas that behave somewhat similarly to the lamb quotas already defined, though not precisely the same – please take care also to note the differences between these quotas and the core WTO beef quotas described later in this document that behave quite differently and use associations for very different purposes.
The quotas used in the EUs are:


097308 and 097300 (Central America)
097314 and 097315 (Nicaragua)
097209 and 097210 (Peru)

Using the C. America quotas as an example, the following data is set up – replicated for Nicaragua and Peru, though the Peru commodity codes are more specific:


In summary
This effectively means that every single good imported on these three quotas is treated as being 1.421 times its actual weight – other than convention, it is not clear why the quota volumes were just not set differently in the first place. Each of the underlying regulations features a footnote re: beef products as follows:
“Expressed in carcase weight equivalent as follows: 100 kg of bone-in meat shall be equivalent to 70 kg1 of boneless meat.”
Eggs from Mexico (TBC)


There are two EU main quotas related to egg products currently in place, that utilise an equivalent association to determine the declarable weight of goods, depending on the commodity type.
The two main quotas  09.1832 and 09.1869, respectively for egg yolks or eggs not in shell and egg albumin, use the equivalence association to calculate egg weights according to the UCC code calculation


Bison from Canada (TBC)



The arrangement that the EU has for the importation of bison from Canada is very similar to that used on WTO quotas from multiple countries worldwide
Please note that, at the time of writing, the Canada (CETA) trade agreement has not been carried over to the UK Tariff and is not imminent.
The idea is to differentiate between different cuts of meat: those considered of higher value and those considered of lower value
Quota associations are applied to provide an equivalence for the various product types, as follows: 


Key examples - Normal associations (NM)Beef WTO quotas


There are a number of quotas that have been set up to facilitate the trade in beef products according to the EU’s WTO schedule.
The primary quota arrangement caters for imports from the following origins:


Argentina
Australia
Canada
New Zealand
United States of America
Uruguay

The quota is an annual quota split into 4 equal quarters running from:


1st July to 30th September
1st October to 31st December
1st January to 31st March
1st April to 30th June


Main quota = 09.2201, sub quota = 09.2202 Regulation R0481/12 – Beef (AR, CA, US, UY, AU, NZ)
COMMISSION IMPLEMENTING REGULATION (EU) No 481/2012 of 7 June 2012 laying down rules for the management of a tariff quota for high-quality beef.

Article 2 - Management of the tariff quota


The tariff quota shall be managed on a first-come, first- served basis in accordance with Articles 308a and 308b and Article 308c(1) of Regulation (EEC) No 2454/93. No import licences shall be required. 
The tariff quota shall be managed as a parent tariff quota under order number 09.2201 with four quarterly sub-tariff quotas under order number 09.2202.  The benefit from the tariff quota can be granted only by applying for order number 09.2202 referring to the sub-tariff quotas. 
The drawings on the sub-tariff quotas until 30 September, 31 December and 31 March shall be stopped respectively on the fifth working day of the Commission in November, February and May. Their unused balances shall be added to the quantities for the quarterly sub-tariff quotas starting respectively on 1 October, 1 January and 1 April. No unused balance at the end of a quota year shall be transferred to another quota year. 


Parent quota order number and definitions


Original quota order number 09.2201 was set up from 1st July 2012 with an empty validity end date
Parent quota 09.2201 set up with definition periods one per year, running from 1st July to 30th June – for some reason this only started in 2015, not 2012.


Child quota order number and definitions


Original child quota order number 09.2202 also set up from 1st July 2012 with an empty validity end date
4 definitions per year on 09.2202, running from:


1st July to 30th September
1st October to 31st December
1st January to 31st March
1st April to 30th June





There are quota associations between the parent 09.2201 and child 09.2202 quota definitions
These associations are made on each quota definition with type NM (normal) and coefficient of 1.0000
The 4 sub-quota definition periods are associated with the single annual parent quota definition (repeated [marketing]-yearly – July to June)
This year, a total volume of 45000000.00 KGM is assigned to the parent: this is split into 4 equal chunks of 11250000.00 KGM for each sub-quota period


Main quota definition (parent)


Sub quota definitions (child)


All measures are set against the sub quota 09.2202
As per the regulation, the benefit from the tariff quota can be granted only by applying for order number 09.2202 referring to the sub-tariff quotas.
There are no measures against the parent quota 09.2201.
The start and end dates of the measures line up with the start and end dates of the quota definitions

Purpose of beef quota associations


The purpose of the beef quota associations is to ensure that any balance left over at the end of a quota definition period is made available to the subsequent definition period within that marketing year.
For example balance from quarter 1 can be carried forward into quarter 2, from Q2 into Q3 and from Q3 into Q4
Balance may not be carried forward from year to year however.
Although it may seem that this function is thematically detached from the nature of the quota association, this is just how the border systems function in response: QAM (HMRC’s border system’s Quota Allocation Module) has been constructed to allow for this specific functionality


Orange juice from Israel


The Israel orange juice quota association is designed to limit the import of a certain range of orange juice commodity codes into the EU (and in future the UK). As per the diagram to the right, taken from the EU’s regulation 1154/2009, main quota 09.1331 is set up to accept a large volume (35,000 tonnes) of all orange juice commodities
Sub quota 09.1333 is set up to allow a max of 21,280 tonnnes of juice in smaller containers
Due to the association, when a trader brings in goods against either of the quotas, the main quota is decremented: when the sub quota (small containers) is exhausted, traders may still continue to bring goods in on the main quota, provided they are not the commodities that identify small containers of orange juice.
This quota is set up with relation type NM (Normal – restrictive to main quota), such that a quantitive limit is applied to the sub quota
The coefficient is set to 1.00000, meaning that drawing down 1kg on the subquota will also draw down 1kg on the parent with no equivalence calculation.



Steel safeguards – most of the world
Background to steel safeguards


In 2017, POTUS applied a swingeing import duty on steel, aluminium and tin goods coming into the USA from most overseas countries, in an avowed attempt to save the US steel industry from ‘dumping’ of cheap steel from abroad. This duty remains in place to this day.
The impact on global steel trade has been dramatic – suddenly, all the steel which would have found a buyer on the US market could not be sold, and traders needed to find a buyer. This therefore led to an immediate and hugely distorted over-supply of goods from overseas onto the EU market.
Therefore the EU introduced similar measures, in the first year a replica of the US charges, but in the second, as it became clear that the balance of trade was complex to introduce, as well as facing into a potential trade dispute from nations that had done no wrong, the EU introduced a complex quota-based system to ensure that the volume of such goods coming into the Union was appropriately balanced.
This quota system has since become even more nuanced, resulting in the new measures introduced in October 2019, on which the UK will be basing our response.

Steel safeguards and quota associations


The steel safeguards are broken into 28 product categories, of which c. 20 will be carried over into the UK’s safeguard response.
Categories 1, 13 and 16 are special and require quota associations to ensure that the policy is executed to its fullest.
Before detailing this, it is worth reiterating how the DIT and HMRC systems connect and how this changes from the current setup with the EU.
The important piece to note here is that the UK will be allocating its own quotas after EU Exit, and not the EU.
HMRC has introduced a new system called QAM (Quota Allocation Module) which allocates quota requests on importers’ declarations.
Any new functionality needs to be coded from scratch in the UK: safeguard quotas are such new functionality: as it stands (Dec 19), CDS is not yet ready to allocate this kind of quota association.


What’s special about steel safeguards?
The EU introduced a new concept for steel safeguards that ensures that a maximum volume is assigned to imports from individual countries; i.e. a single country cannot dominate a quota to the exclusion of all others – the purpose is to maintain some kind of equitable trade flow across the globe.

How does this work?


A main quota is set up with a large, globally available volume;
Multiple sub-quotas are set up with volumes that are a specific percentage of the parent (but in total add up to significantly more that the parent’s total)
In this real example (EU category 13), imports from no country are allowed to exceed 33.33%; hence the main quota is set up with 100% (141,103,760.00 KGM), and 6 sub-quotas are set up with 33.33% (42,331,128.00 KGM)




Safeguard national limits are artificial – they cannot be applied to every single countryThey are applied solely to those countries that are liable to exceed the mandated threshold via a NM-type sub quota association

UK interpretation of steel safeguards
The UK is likely to interpret the steel safeguards regulation as follows:

Category 1 - Non Alloy and Other Alloy Hot Rolled Sheets and Strips 


All year round, there will be a limit of 75% max per country limit applied to quotas applied to category 1.
The expectation is that the EU will be the only bloc that threatens to get near this 75% limit.


Category 13 - Rebars & Category 16 - Non Alloy and Other Alloy Wire Rod
 


The steel safeguard year runs from July 1st to June 30th. The year is typically broken into 4 quarters (July to Sep, Oct to Dec, Jan to Mar, Apr to Jun).
For these categories, there will be no association of quotas, as the max does not apply, however on quarter 4, Apr to Jun, the ‘global’ quota will be opened up to other large exporters which will have a maximum 30% threshold applied, as per the EU example 2 slides prior to this.
As previously described, this cannot yet be managed via allocation in QAM, though the solution is in delivery.
The UK will set up quota associations in the same way as the EU does once the functionality has been delivered.

C. America quota of quotas
Quota of quota – clothes from C. America



Applicable to Nicaragua and El Salvador, a function known as a ‘quota of quotas’ has been implemented to apply a maximum import volume across multiple quotas.
The intent is expressed as follows:For the tariff quotas with quota order numbers from 09.7105 to 09.7138, the global yearly quota volume may not exceed the following number of items (pairs) for the respective calendar year.with a table beneath it expressing the maximum overall volume across multiple quotas.
There are two such quotas of quotas for Nicaragua and a single quota of quota for El Salvador.
Please note – this requirement is more theoretical than practical: it has not been implemented in the EU tariff since 2015, and although the data appears to be present for 2020, it may yet be removed as unnecessary - i.e. it is understood as a regulatory requirement, however the legislated volumes are never even close to being met, therefore the function is disabled.




There is a single quota (or quota of quotas) to which a master overall volume is assigned. For 2020, the volumes are 12,687,500 items of clothing from Nicaragua.
Crucially, this is purely a blanket quota exercising a maximum threshold: there are no commodities applied to the master quota: traders are also not expected to reference 09.7104 on their declarations.
The quota then has a NM type relationship with the 34 individual quotas that are afforded a threshold by the main quota. On the diagram, there is only one line, but there are 34 individual associations.
Quota volumes are applied to the individual quotas, as are related commodities.
For 2020, according to legislation, the sum of the initial quota volumes for the 34 quotas is 28,854,000.00 items (the overall Quota of Quota maximum is c. 43% of this).

Tomatoes from Morocco & Western Sahara – a little bit special


The EU’s COMMISSION IMPLEMENTING REGULATION (EU) No 812/2012 of 12 September 2012 amending Council Regulation (EC) No 747/2001 as regards tariff quotas of the Union for certain agricultural and processed agricultural products originating in Morocco introduced legislation that caused a great deal of complexity with regard to quota associations that has no parallel in the Tariff.
It has been decided to not carry this over into the UK Tariff, as the complexities of adminstering the quotas are not warranted: the UK’s tomato agriculture is far less vital to the economy than equivalents in Southern Europe, which were served by this policy.
There are two main features of the Moroccan quotas which are rarely replicated elsewhere:


firstly, there are multiple subquotas to a single main quota, described on the screens below
secondly, a unique ‘topup’ mechanism exists to feed one quota with balance from another quota, if such a remainder exists

If that were not complex enough, it also uses the Entry Price System to work out the applicable in quota duties.
The legislation is documented in detail on the following pages.

Regulation R0812/12 – Tomatoes (Morocco)
COMMISSION IMPLEMENTING REGULATION (EU) No 812/2012 of 12 September 2012 amending Council Regulation (EC) No 747/2001 as regards tariff quotas of the Union for certain agricultural and processed agricultural products originating in Morocco

Article 3a - Special provisions for the tariff quotas for tomatoes originating in Morocco (and later Western Sahara)
For tomatoes of CN code 0702 00 00 placed into free circulation in every period from 1 October to 31 May (hereinafter “marketing year”), drawings on the monthly tariff quotas laid down in Annex II under order number 09.1104 from 1 October to 31 December and from 1 January to 31 March respectively, shall be stopped each year on 15 January and on the second working day in the Commission following 1 April.
On the following working day in the Commission, the Commission services will determine the unused balance of each of these tariff quotas and will make available that unused balance within the additional tariff quota applicable for that marketing year under the order number 09.1112.
From the dates on which the monthly tariff quotas are stopped, any retroactive drawings from any of the stopped monthly tariff quotas applicable during the months of November, December and January to March, and any returns of unused volumes to any of the stopped monthly tariff quotas shall be made on the additional tariff quota applicable under the order number 09.1112 for that marketing year.

Master quota order number


Quota order number 09.1104 is set up from June 2005 with 8 definition periods running from start of November to end of May (1 month each)


Parent quota order number and definitions


Original quota order number 09.1112 was set up from 1st Nov 2003. This was superseded in the following years but effectively has been live since then with no validity end date
Parent quota 09.1112 has been set up with definition periods one per year, running for 7 months each from 1st Nov to 31st May ever since 2004.


Child quota order number and definitions


Child quota order number 09.1193 was set up on 1st November 2012 – single record only
Child order number 09.1193 has 7 order definitions per marketing year (start of Nov to end of May) – these are all monthly, running in these periods:


1st Nov to 30th Nov
1st Dec to 31st Dec
1st Jan to 31st Jan
1st Feb to 28th Feb (or 29th)
1st Mar to 31st Mar
1st Apr to 30th Apr
1st May to 31st May




Quota associations
For marketing year 1st Nov 2017 to 31st May 2018 (and replicated thereafter), each of the sub-quota’s definitions (from 09.1193) are associated to the parent definition (09.1112) for that year.



We will be abandoning this complexity, as the import of tomatoes into the UK is not as emotive or so vital for UK tomato growers’ ability to flourish.
We will continue to use two quotas, but both without associations, 09.1104 and 09.1193 running for 8 and 7 months respectively with single definition periods (and hence a single quota volume each accessible throughout that entire period)

Certificates


Introduction to certificates


User needs - certificates


Business rules - certificates


Introduction to certificatesWhat are certificates?
The certificates tables in TARIC-based applications store all of the certificates, licences and other conditions that are referenced via measure conditions in order to make the import (or export) of a good conditional on the provision of some entity.
The sole purpose of certificates in this system is to associate them to measures via measure conditions – on their own, they no value and are not exposed to traders via any other means.
This entity is usually a physical or digital document of some description (e.g. a license or official certificate), but it may also be a non-paper condition - the term “certificate” to label the table is definitely more constrictive than the actual subject matter.
A good example of the ‘non-document’ condition is “Y037 - Goods exempted from the prohibition – biathlon equipment’ where the condition references a property of the good being imported, and not an accompanying document.
These oddities are typically linked to measures using the measure_condition_code “Y”. Please read the instruction guide on measure conditions for a detailed insight.

What certificates are not


A certificate is not a representation of the actual document itself
Our database stores only a certificate code (4 digits) and a description of that code
There is no instruction on where to find that document (if the certificate represents an actual document), there is no link to a URL nor guidance on how to complete the certificate
This could be construed as a flaw in the public-facing aspect of the certification model.
There is a feeling of ‘so what’ when confronted with the need for a certificate – the interaction may favour traders that know certification inside out and the regulations that underpin it, but for entryists, the concept can be bewildering
DIT may consider extending the model to allow more information than just a code and basic description to be stored against the certificate, bearing in mind that the majority of such documents or other entities would likely be owned by Defra or on occasion HMRC

Structure of certificates & certificate types



Much like footnotes and additional codes, certificates are made up of a type code and then a specific code, which, when concatenated, form the unique code of the certificate.
For example, the footnote C656 is constructed of a type code © and a specific certificate code (656) – the entire certificate is known as C656.
Certificate type codes are always 1 digit in length and can be any alphanumeric character (upper case). Historically the alphabetical certificate type codes have been used for EU-wide certificates: the numeric certificate type codes are used for national measures.
Certificate codes typically use numeric IDs, running from 001 to 999 can be reused across multiple certificate type codes. While the schema also allows for alphabetical certificate codes, these are rarely used: there are 11 instances of certificate codes using alpha instead of numeric digits.
Certificate codes must be 3 digits in length.

28.title: Geographical areas
28.content:
Geographical areas


Introduction to geographical areas


Geographical area membership


Key user needs – geographical area


Key business processing rules – geographical areas


Introduction to geographical areas

All measures must be assigned to a single geographical area entity.
This entity, derived from the geographical_areas view may itself be:


a single country (like Namibia)
a group of countries (like Cariforum [a Caribbean trading bloc])
a region – which is a slight misnomer, meaning as it does a country that has yet to be 
fully incorporated, like Kosovo, which remains partially recognised.

A quota though may be assigned to multiple geographical area entities. While this is the case in the EU, the UK is trying to abandon this, for example there is a wine quota (09.1530) in use for the West Balkan countries1 that is going to be split into 6 individual quotas post-implementation period.
A geographical area that is defined as being a country group will have one or more countries (or regions) designated as members of that country group.

Identifying geographical areas


An identifier for a country group (geographical_area_id) is structured depending on the type of area in question.
The geographical code field dictates what type of geographical area is involved:


0 Country
1 Country group
2 Region

For all countries and regions, the code is a 2-digit upper-case alphabetical string


For countries, this is based on the international standard (ISO_3166-1) (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1_alpha-2)
For regions, i.e. unincorporated states, the code is typically a 2-digit string beginning with X, followed by the first letter of the country. e.g. as an upshot of the splintering of the former Yugoslavia, Serbia and Kosovo were formed as ‘regions’, not countries: Serbia = XS, Kosovo = XK. Even though Serbia is now a fully recognised sovereign state, it remains a region (practical implications of flipping; Kosovo is still officially considered to be a part of Serbia by over half the world).

For country groups, the code is an alpha-numeric string of 4-digits.


For country groups set up by the EU, these 4-digit strings are always numeric, e.g. 1001 = Erga Omnes (whole world)
For nationally setup groups (historically managed by HMRC), the groups are alpha-numeric, for example F006 (Phytosanitary certificates)


About country groups
The last example on the previous page (F006 Phytosanitary certificates) shows that the country groups do not have to align to an enshrined globally understood trading entity like EU (1011), CARIFORUM (1033) or GSP LDC (2005).
Because the meat and drink of Taric and TAP is to produce measures, which can be connected to just one single geographical area, it is often simpler just to create a group of countries and apply the measure to the group and not the individual countries.
This can often be at the expense of making total sense however. For example, to execute the regulations associated with handloomed products, a group has been set up to accommodate the countries to which a quota applies for such products – the name of the group is “Silk or cotton handloom products”.

Geographical area membershipGeographical areas that represent country groups (area code 1) are designed to include member countries
A geographical area group can only contain regions or countries (area codes 0 and 2), not other geographical area groups – any attempt to assign a country group to another country group as a member must not be permitted and cause a business rule failure at HMRC. A geographical area’s membership of a country group is bookended by a start date and potentially and end date, where absolutely required.
While geographical areas are absolutely not a volatile area within the application, and the changes are few and far between, there are a number of use cases where membership does change, albeit infrequently. For example, countries move in and out of GSP tiers from year to year as their progress or decline economically.
Steel safeguards work on country groups created specifically for the purpose of applying punitive duties against large numbers of countries; these groups tend to change from year to year, as we learn more about the impact of the punitive duties on trade flows.
The UK may choose to create country groups to apply specific regulatory controls.
Relationship of measures to geographical areas


All measures are assigned to precisely one geographical area.
That area may be a country, region (non-incorporated country) or a group of countries.
If the geographical area is a country group, then it is possible to exclude (one or more) members of that country group from the measure via inclusion in the measure_excluded_geographical_areas table.
The excluded country must be a member of that group.
Please note: both the excluded_geographical_area and geographical_area_id fields refer to the excluded country, not the group.

Relationship of quotas to geographical areas


All quotas need to be represented both as measures and within the structures related to quotas.
With licensed quotas, these are only represented by quotas.
The relationship of geographical areas to quotas needs to be reflected in both the measures and quotas structures (except for licensed quotas).
Therefore both the relationship of quotas to their origins and measures to the related geographical areas needs to be managed and synchronised in the data creation.

Relationship with measures





GA6
Loops in the parent relation between geographical areas and parent geographical area groups are not allowed. If a geographical area A is a parent geographical area group of B then B cannot be a parent geographical area group of A (loops can also exist on more than two levels, e.g. level 3; If A is a parent of B and B is a parent of C then C cannot be a parent of A).
Not required
Won’t Have - As above


GA7
The validity period of geographical area must not overlap any other geographical area with the same geographical area id.
Required This should be handled at the same time as GA1 (above)
Won’t Have


GA10
When a geographical area is referenced in a measure then the validity period of the geographical area must span the validity period of the measure.
Required
Must Have - Unless explicitly required, a geographical area should be left open-ended to avoid this error – there is rarely a need to terminate a country group, especially as there is no public-facing aspect to this: however, in certain cases, e.g. a regularly refreshed pseudo-group (like used for steel safeguards) or countries whose borders have shifted as a result of wars (Serbia and Montenegro), this is still required. It is vital however that end dates are applied sparingly.


GA11
If a geographical area is referenced as an excluded geographical area in a measure then the membership period of the (excluded) geographical area must span the validity period of the measure.
Required
Must Have - As above – this is typically avoided by NOT end-dating geographical areas


Relation with geographical area membership





GA12
The referenced geographical area id (member) must exist.
Required
Must Have


GA13
The referenced geographical area id (member) can only be linked to a country or region (area code = 0 or 2).
Required
Must Have


GA14
The referenced geographical area group id must exist.
Required
Must Have


GA15
The membership start date must be less than or equal to the membership end date.
Required
Must Have


GA16
The validity period of the geographical area group must span all membership periods of its members.
Required
Must Have


GA17
The membership period of a geographical area (member) must be within (inclusive) the validity period of the geographical area group (geographical area’s start and end date).
Required
Must Have


GA18
When a geographical area is more than once member of the same group then there may be no overlap in their membership periods.
Required
Must Have


GA19
If the associated geographical area group has a parent geographical area group then all the members of the geographical area group must also be members of the parent geographical area group.
Required
Must Have - But avoid creating parent groups, or terminating existing parent groups


GA20
If the associated geographical area group has a parent geographical area group then the membership period of each member of the parent group must span the membership period of the same geographical area in the geographical area group.
Required
Must Have But avoid creating parent groups, or terminating existing parent groups


Delete a geographical area





GA21
If a geographical area is referenced in a measure then it may not be deleted1.
Required
Must Have - Though we should never be deleting geographical areas.


GA22
A geographical area cannot be deleted if it is referenced as a parent geographical area group.
Required
Must Have


Delete a geographical area membership





GA23
If a geographical area is referenced as an excluded geographical area in a measure, the membership association with the measure geographical area group cannot be deleted.
Required
Must Have

29.content:
Nomenclature


Background


Managing goods classification – user needs


Key business rules


BackgroundCombined Nomenclature, Harmonised System - Structure

HS - Harmonised System


The first six digits of the code numbers of the tariff or TARIC have been regulated by the World Customs Organization (WCO) in the form of the HS nomenclature world-wide since 1988.
HS is currently used in 176 countries. A revision takes place regularly, roughly every 5 years (so far, 1996, 2002, 2007, 2012, 2017). Next change anticipated in 2022.


CN - Combined Nomenclature


The “Combined Nomenclature” is published in the Official Journal of the European Community in October each year and specifies the first eight digits of the Tariff/Taric, as well as third country tariff rates for the following year. This eight-digit nomenclature can not be changed over a period of one year and applies both in the EU and the Associated States (BG, RO, TR, etc.).


TARIC - Tarif Intégré Communautaire / Tarif intégré des Communautés européennes


Taric, the tariff rate of the European Communities, is the same as the CN in the first eight digits. There is, therefore, a uniform marking for customs purposes and statistics. The Taric is subdivided however by the Taric sub-positions (from the ninth place) more deeply.
As the combined nomenclature is not sufficiently detailed to support the community tariff and commercial legislation, the 8-digit codes can be broken down into 10-digit codes called “TARIC codes”. 
These codes are created at any time, according to the legislative needs.


Harmonised system sections


The Harmonised System is categorised into sections and chapters
The section is a logical grouping that is not reflected in the nomenclature.
Each chapter, which is a subdivision of a section, is fully self-contained within the logical section.
Sections are represented by Roman numerals (1 to 21 / I to XXI)



        
          
ID
Description


I

II
Vegetable   products (chapter 6 - 14)

IX

X

Description

Footwear,   headgear, umbrellas, sun umbrellas, walking-sticks, seat-sticks, whips,   riding-crops and parts thereof; prepared feathers and articles made   therewith; artificial flowers; articles of human hair (chapter 64 - 67)


XIII
Articles   of stone, plaster, cement, asbestos, mica or similar materials; ceramic   products; glass and glassware (chapter 68 - 70)


XIV
Natural   or cultured pearls, precious or semi-precious stones, precious metals, metals   clad with precious metal and articles thereof; imitation jewellery; coins   (chapter 71)

Base   metals and articles of base metal (chapter 72 - 83)


XVI
Machinery   and mechanical appliances; electrical equipment; parts thereof, sound   recorders and reproducers, television image and sound recorders and   reproducers, and parts and accessories of such articles (chapter 84 - 85)
