Miscellaneous   manufactured articles (chapter 94 - 96)


XXI
Works   of art, collectors’ pieces and antiques (chapter 97 - 99)


        
      Concept definition & terminology 2


The UK refers to the full list of products in the UK Tariff as the Goods Classification – this is synonymous with the broad name for the full list of products: goods nomenclature or just nomenclature.
In the EU, this is referred to under multiple names: often the EU refers to the Tariff as the “Combined Nomenclature” (CN), though officially this refers only to the first 8 digits of the code.
Within the broader body, the individual elements referring to specific products are called commodity codes.
The commodity code is what is entered into the SAD (C88) form – the Single Administrative Document that acts as the import declaration form – see ringed box to the right.
There is a total of 24,504 commodity codes (as of 1st December 2019): of these 15,887 are declarable end-lines (see definition later).


There are three key concepts to understand in this section. All of these have a significant impact on the measures that can be defined and managed by Tariff Managers:


commodity codes
product line suffixes
indents


Commodity codes, product line suffixes and indents in practice


The schematic to the right illustrates a ‘hierarchy’ starting from the very first commodity code in the Tariff (0100 00 00 00) down to the last end-line under the 1st major HS heading branch (0101 90 00 00), i.e. Live horses, asses, mules and hinnies
This shows the commodity codes, split into segments for ease of reading, the product line suffix and the indent, as well as the current description of the commodity code.
The physical indent on the description matches the indent field.
Hence, Horses is a ‘child’ of ‘Live horses, asses, mules and hinnies’ and ‘Pure-bred breeding animals’ is a child of ‘Horses’ – however these relationships are inferred, not explicit.
You will notice that there are two zeroes at the start of the tree – this is a slightly bewildering treatment from the EU, but we need to work with it: the HS chapter and the HS heading both use an indent of 0. This will not be of huge immediate interest, as these codes will not change until the lead-up to January 2022.


If one were to try and print out the whole commodity tree (c. 24,500 lines), you would:


select the commodity codes with current validity
sort them by commodity code and then product line suffix
indent them using the indent field

Declarability and measure assignment


A SAD form requires that the trader enter the most detailed description possible for the good that is being traded, not something vague like ‘Horses’
There are two rules that define whether or not a good is declarable, i.e. whether or not it can be entered onto a SAD form:
first, a good must have a product line suffix (PLS) of “80”: anything else cannot be traded – these commodity codes are in the database purely as structural fillers
second, a good must be an end-line aka a leaf. i.e. it must not have any children.
In the example to the left, the declarable commodities are those with a      against them
Although 0101 29 00 00, 01010 00 00 00 and 0101 00 00 00 all have a PLS of “80”, they all have child codes underneath them, therefore cannot be declared.




In the example above (red marquee), it is interesting to note (and this is key in understanding where a product line suffix other than “80” is used), that there are two items with the commodity code 0101 21 00 00.
One has a PLS of 10, the other has a PLS of 80.
This is common and is likely to be a treatment we need to get used to in the UK for future change.

Jams and jellies are very complex



The image above shows the complexity of certain hierarchies.
The indent numbers have been doctored slightly to show the true number of indents, ignoring the double zero noted previously.
There are actually 14 tiers of data in certain points in the hierarchy, as shown here
This is exceptional however
Please also note the apparently inconsistent use of product line suffixes: why has 2007 99 39 00 got a PLS of “80” when it is clearly an intermediate code?
The answer seems to be that the non-80 code is used where there is a need to insert a structural heading with the same commodity code as the subsequent code, presumably due to space restrictions in the hierarchy.

Smashing preconceptions on hierarchical inheritance



This is undoubtedly an unusually complex tree, however it does illustrate well a concept that needs to be understood, to help the Tariff management team to grasp the idea of inheritance, which is critical in measure management.
The 10-digit commodity code is divided into 5 pairs of digits.
While it is alluring to consider that these two digit pairs provide enough information to work out the hierarchy, this is coincidental, though, certainly at the top of the hierarchy, frequently true.

There are five main reasons why new commodities are required
New commodities - examples

Do not underestimate WCO changes



The graph to the left shows the peaks and troughs of nomenclature management over the last 10 years
The 2 big peaks are on 1st Jan 2012 and 1st Jan 2017, the to dates in the last 10 years where the WCO has made alterations to their HS6 structures.
Every non-WCO year follows a similar peak / trough structure
Big peak in Jan (annual CN code changes, smaller peak in July (new suspension), ad hoc for the rest of the year
2019 has been an outlier, as commodity code changes have taken place throughout the year

January 2022 will require a lot of preparation

WCO 5-year changes are significant



This shows the change from 31st December to 2nd January on just a small branch 0305 59 00
Most of these changes were deletions, not creations.
The spike of 2,334 was more like 4,500 actual changes

WCO HS correlation tables



Here is a page from a 60-page correlation table document, comparing the HS systems of 2012 and 2017
The WCO specify the changes that are made to the 4 and 6 digit codes that they master.
But … the majority of the change is felt lower down the hierarchy.
You move a parent, you have to move the children.
And in moving a child, you have to give it a new commodity code, due to the need to sequence by comm code and pls.
This really means ending an old comm code and creating a new 



How will we decide on new commodity codes? How will we facilitate alignment with the EU?The answer has to be that we follow the EU’s changed precisely
There are two additional concepts that are useful to know, but play a far smaller part in the management of goods classification. Origins and successorsare intended to create an audit trail when commodity codes change

Origins
Origins


An origin defines the commodity code from which a new commodity code was derived.
When a commodity code is split into two, the ‘origin’ of the two (or more) new commodity codes is the parent commodity code.




In the example above, a successor will have been created for codes 2001 90 70 10 and 2001 90 70 90 of2001 90 70 00.
It is mandatory that at least one origin is created for every new commodity code
However, this data is of zero value to the Tariff Application

Successors


An successor defines the commodity code into which an existing commodity code has been absorbed.
It is not mandatory for a successor code to be created, though they may be created.

Residual codes


The sweet peppers example can also be used to exemplify residual codes.
A residual code is the code usually labelled ’Other’ which is created when a code is split into a specific and remainder part.
In this example 2001 90 70 00 is split into 2 child codes.


The specific code is assigned 10 as the final 2 digits.
The residual code is assigned 90 as the final 2 digits.
If in future more child codes as added to the parent as siblings to 10 and 90, then these are assigned 20, 30, 40 etc as the final 2 digits, while space remains.





If a code is split on the last digit, rather than the last 2 digits, it is usually split into 1 and 9, for example:




There are more than 6,500 residual codes in the database

#
Rule
Notes


NIG1
The validity period of the goods nomenclature must not   overlap any other goods nomenclature with the same goods code. Two   nomenclatures overlap if they have the same goods code and a time overlap in   their validity periods.
Mandatory – priority high   Commodity codes are uniquely identified by their SID value.   There cannot be more than one entity with the same SID. There can however be   more than one entity with the same compound key of commodity code and product   line suffix, provided the multiple items do not coexist concurrently. The use   case here is that a commodity code has previously been terminated, and then   reinstituted at a later date with the same commodity code and product line   suffix. This rule states that there must be no crossover in the dates of   these entities that shar the same commodity code and product line suffix.


NIG2
The validity period of the goods nomenclature must be   within (inclusive) the validity period of the product line above in the   hierarchy.
Mandatory – priority high   If terminating a commodity code, you must have already   done the same to the child commodity codes.


NIG3
For lines having a product line suffix equal to   “80”, the validity period of the goods nomenclature must span the   validity period of the line(s) below in the hierarchy.
Mandatory – priority high   This is essentially the same as NIG2


NIG4
The start date of the goods nomenclature must be less than   or equal to the end date.
Mandatory – priority high   As per rule description



Goods   nomenclature origin



NIG5
When creating a goods nomenclature code, at least one   “derived from”‘ code must be created.   This rule is only applicable to update extractions.
Mandatory – priority high   The origin should be the code from which the commodity is   derived (i.e. its parent) if the use case id the creation of a new commodity   code from a parent, e.g. for splitting a commodity code into two.   If the use case concerns moving chunks of or single   commodity codes from one place in the hierarchy to another , then the   requirement is that the origin should be the identifier of the code which   used to represent the commodity in question


NIG7
The “derived from” code, if entered, must be a   goods nomenclature which exists and is applicable the day before the start   date of the new code entered.
Mandatory – priority high   as per rule



Goods   nomenclature successor



NIG10
The “absorbed by” code, if entered, must be a   goods nomenclature which exists and is applicable the day after the closing   date.
Mandatory – priority high   as per rule, however there are no rules which state that   successors must be entered, though it remains a good idea to do so



Goods nomenclature indent



NIG11
At least one indent record is mandatory. The start date of   the first indentation must be equal to the start date of the nomenclature. No   two associated indentations may have the same start date. The start date must   be less than or equal to the end date of the nomenclature.
Mandatory – priority high   as per rule



Goods description and description periods



NIG12
At least one description is mandatory. The start date of   the first description period must be equal to the start date of the   nomenclature. No two associated description periods may have the same start   date. The start date must be less than or equal to the end date of the   nomenclature.
Mandatory – priority high   as per rule



Nomenclature group membership



NIG13
The nomenclature groups that are referenced must exist.
Not required   We will not be using nomenclature groups


NIG14
The start date of the group association must be less than   or equal to the end date.
Not required   We will not be using nomenclature groups


NIG15
The period of the association with a nomenclature group   must be within (inclusive) the validity period of the nomenclature.
Not required   We will not be using nomenclature groups


NIG16
The period of the association with a nomenclature group   must be within (inclusive) the validity period of the nomenclature group.
Not required   We will not be using nomenclature groups


NIG17
When the same goods nomenclature occurs more than once as   a member of the same group then there must be no overlap in their membership   periods.
Not required   We will not be using nomenclature groups


NIG50
If the referenced nomenclature group is an ERN   nomenclature group (group code = ‘X’), then the nomenclature   code must be a CN (level 8 or higher).
Not required   We will not be using nomenclature groups



Footnote association



NIG18
Footnotes with a footnote type for which the application   type = “CN footnotes” must be linked to CN lines (all codes up to 8   digits).
Mandatory – priority low   This is a peculiarity that should be consigned to   history – we should imply not use footnotes of this type in the future. The   proposal is for all future footnotes to belong to the new footnote type of “FC”,   which will assignable to any commodity code, regardless of ‘depth’, so that   daft rules such as this do not need to be run - see the notes on new footnote   types in the footnotes manual.


NIG19
Footnotes with a footnote type for which the application   type = “TARIC footnotes” can be associated at any level.
Mandatory – priority low   The “FC” type, mentioned above would be of a type with   the application code “Taric footnotes”, therefore can be assigned to any   commodity code, regardless of its depth.


NIG20
Footnotes that are referenced must exist.
Mandatory – priority high   User must only be able to select existing footnotes


NIG21
The start date of the association with a footnote  must be less than or equal to the end date   of the association.
Mandatory – priority medium   as per rule, but in most cases there is no need to   end-date a footnote to commodity code association.


NIG22
The period of the association with a footnote must be   within (inclusive) the validity period of the nomenclature.
Mandatory – priority medium   as per rule, but in most cases there is no need to   end-date a footnote to commodity code association.


NIG23
The period of the association with a footnote must be   within (inclusive) the validity period of the footnote.
Mandatory – priority medium   as per rule, but in most cases there is no need to   end-date a footnote to commodity code association.


NIG24
When the same footnote is associated more than once with   the same nomenclature then there may be no overlap in their association   periods.
Mandatory – priority medium   as per rule, but in most cases there is no need to   end-date a footnote to commodity code association.


NIG37
The validity period of the footnote type must span the   validity period of the footnote association.
Optional   Footnote types typically do not get end-dated and we   should retain that maxim



Relation with measures



NIG30
When a goods nomenclature is used in a goods measure then   the validity period of the goods nomenclature    must span the validity period of the goods measure.
Mandatory – priority high   as per rule


NIG31
When a goods nomenclature is used in an additional   nomenclature measure then the validity period of the goods nomenclature must   span the validity period of the additional nomenclature measure (the   additional nomenclature measure links together a goods nomenclature and an   additional code).
Mandatory – priority high   as per rule – this concerns (primarily) trade remedy   measures (anti-dumping and anti-subsidy measures) that feature both a   commodity code and an additional code.



Relation with Export Refund codes (ERNs)



NIG32
When a goods nomenclature is used in an Export Refund   nomenclature then the validity period of the goods nomenclature must span the   validity period of the Export Refund nomenclature.
Not required   We will not be using ERNs



Delete a goods nomenclature code



NIG34
A goods nomenclature cannot be deleted if it is used in a   goods measure.
Mandatory – priority medium   as per rule, though we should honestly not be deleting   commodity codes, just terminating them


NIG35
A goods nomenclature cannot be deleted if it is used in an   additional nomenclature measure.
Mandatory – priority medium   as per rule, though we should honestly not be deleting   commodity codes, just terminating them


NIG36
A goods nomenclature cannot be deleted if it is used in an   Export refund nomenclature.
Mandatory – priority low   as per rule, though we should honestly not be deleting   commodity codes, just terminating them. Even though we are not using ERNs,   this rule could trip us up.

30.title: Measure types
30.content:
Measure types


Introduction to measure types


Measure type fields


Logical view of measure types


Relationship of measure types to additional code types


Data structures


Screen designs - footnotes


Key user needs - footnotes


Key business rules - footnotes


Introduction to measure typesStructure of measure types


Each measure belongs to exactly one measure type. The measure types describe to the border systems how to execute some kind of action on the trade in question (e.g. charge a duty / require a document).
While the data associated with a measure type is a pretty good explainer of what the measure is intended to do, there is a significant amount of work to be done by HMRC to make the measure behave as intended.




This is even more important when one considers the continuing role that CHIEF will play during the dual running of the two border systems - CHIEF is unable to extend its measure type capability without programming: at least CDS can be configured to extend its measure type list.


Any changes to measures, additions of new measures will need to be agreed by HMRC in advance – their function cannot fully be described in Taric: see anomaly of measure type 696 (used in steel safeguards) below.
Regulation groups, measure types and Box 36 of the SAD form


In the regulation training manual, we mentioned the need for regulations to be assigned to the right regulation groups, because of the correlation required between the regulation group and what the trader enters in Box 36 on the SAD form.
Well the measure type falls into the same bracket – the measure types have to be actively correlated to regulation group IDs by HMRC in CDS.
Therefore, HMRC need to be involved in measure type creation.


Measure types & responsibilities prior to the IP


There are c. 260 measure types in existence prior to the end of the implementation period (IP).
Some of these have not been used in some time and can be considered as dead, even if they are not formally terminated on the database.
c. 80 of these are VAT and excise measures that DIT will never get involved in.
There remain about 100 measure types that will crop up over the course of the next year and will need to be understood, even if some of these are going to be omitted from the UK tariff (at least in the first instance).
The measures that we need to manage can be broadly broken in to the following groups, with the table to the right showing the division of responsibility between the EU and the member states, represented for the UK by HMRC.
These will evolve after the IP (Jan 2021).


        
          
Responsibility

The EU

The   member states (HMRC for the UK)

      Measure types & responsibilities post-IP


After the IP, there will be a great degree of similarity in the applicable trade measures.
The major difference in responsibility will see the MTPO team in DIT’s Trade Policy Group replacing the role of the EU in co-ordinating and maintaining the measures that were previously seen as pan-European.
There are a number of other changes too, as per the notes column
These groups of measure types are detailed in subsequent pages.


Measure type series


Each measure is associated with a single measure type.
Each measure type is in turn associated with a single measure type series, in which additional properties of the measure type and its behaviour are stored, and the application logic for the measure types is sequenced.
The measure type series are put in place to permit multiple means of overlaying measure types (and hence duties) via combination and exclusion.




If modifying measure types were considered dangerous, then modifying measure type series is much more dangerous – it is highly recommended that any work that DIT to represent measure types series is to present a read-only view: there should be no capability to manage the measure type series, as the impact is potentially so damaging.


Measure types series - measure type combination field


The measure type combination field determines how many measure types of a given type series can be applied on a trader’s declaration at any given time to the same context.
There are just two valid options:


        
          
Option
Description


0
Only   1 measure at export and 1 at import from the series


1
All   measure types in the series to be considered


        
      What this does not mean


If measure type combination is set to 0, this does not mean that Tariff managers can only set up a single measure type from each measure types series in the same context.

What this does mean


This does mean that a trader can only take advantage of one measure types from any given series (if combination set to 0).

For example:


These commodities (8802110010, 8802120010, 8802200010, 8802300010, 8802400010) all have both 103 (Third country duty) and 105 (Non-preferential duty under end-use) applied to the same context1.
It is quite possible for a trade agreement to feature both a tariff preference and a preferential quota on the same context (commodity code), but the trader can only call on one of these, not both.
The measure type series identifies how different measures are applied alongside or overlaid.
For example, you cannot apply multiple measures from the same series (the trader must choose), but multiple measures from different series can be overlaid.
Hence, anti-dumping duties (series D) are overlaid on top of MFN duties (series C) - the to coexist, are additive and do not require selection by the trader.

Existing measure type series



This table is important in understanding how Taric-based border systems apply the measures that DIT has supplied.
Firstly, the sequence matters – the alphabetical sequence of measure types series is the sequence in which CDS will look to implement the measures.
Therefore, any complete prohibitions are dealt with first, via measures of type series A (Importation and/or exportation prohibited). If there is a complete prohibition that applies to the specific circumstances of the trade (e.g. the combination of commodity and origin), then that’s that – the trade cannot continue – working out anything else / checking certificates etc is of zero value.
If there is no complete prohibition on the trade, then the next step is to work out if the trader has the necessary conditions in place, including certification or licensing, to allow the trade to pass (type series B). Again, if the necessary documentation or other conditions are not met, there calculating the import duty is somewhat academic.
These two measure type series apply equally to imports / exports.


Thirdly, after application of the prohibitions and restrictions, measure type series C is checked (applicable duty)


Series C contains the MFN duties, tariff preferences, all the quotas and all the suspensions – the trader picks one (actively)
Series D contains the anti-dumping and anti-subsidy duties – of these, if there are multiple that apply to a given context (for example both an anti-subsidy and anti-dumping duty on the same code for the same company), then they both apply: the trader does not get to choose the lower.
Series E and F contain Meursing duties, then we get to …
Series J is the countervailing charge series (officially) – the countervailing charge measure in this group is no longer used (since 2005), leaving just 695 (additional duties) and 696 (additional duties (safeguard)). Safeguards are the exception that prove the rule with regard to applicability duties according to measure type series sequence – this is discussed on the following pages.
Series M features measure types associated with agricultural safeguards, not duties (e.g. the SIV, Unit price)
Skipping N and O (non-duty-related), the next duty-bearing series are VAT and excise (series P and Q), which are applied over and above import duties.
Finally, series S contains the additional duties required by the agricultural safeguards re: chicken and other poultry goods, which are applied over and above any standard duty from series C.

Context - what does this mean?


First thing to say – this is a useful term invented by the project team: it is not a Taric term, but is a handy short hand for what it actually means
Here is a Taric sentence that helps to explain context: this is taken from Taric Business Processing rule ME1:




No two measures that match on all of these fields can coexist – according to this rule, if just one field differs, then a second measure can be inserted.
In fact, the stated rule is not as strict as reality – if there is any crossover of period of application (start & end dates), then the measures will clash.
In addition – conflict checking must also apply all the way up and down a commodity code hierarchy – this is explained below in the pages re: ME32


The measure type 696 anomaly


Measure type 696 is the measure used to impose safeguards on imports of steel from multiple countries around the world, in an attempt to stabilise the flow of steel goods coming into the Union as a result of the USA’s imposition of similar safeguards: the upset to world trade flows caused such a glut of cheep steel to land on EU shores, that the EU had no option other than to follow suit.
Safeguards are made up of two elements: a 25% safeguard additional duty, and a non-preferential quota, which essentially waives the safeguard.




According to the additive rules of thumb re: measure type series, it is unclear by what mechanism the quota (type 122) can cancel out the additional duties (safeguard).
The understanding is that this must have been achieved via some custom configuration in the border systems.

Agri measures


Why there are so many import control measures … ME32


“There may be no overlap in time with other measure occurrences with a goods code in the same nomenclature hierarchy which references the same measure type, geo area, order number, additional code and reduction indicator. This rule is not applicable for Meursing additional codes.”

Jams, fruit jellies, marmalades …



As a tariff manager, I have been asked to create a new measure for ERGA OMNES of type “Import control” at level 4 “with a sugar content exceeding 30% by weight” – 
There is already a measure of type “Import control” at level 8 “Fruit purees obtained by sieving then brought to the boil in a vacuum, the texture and chemical composition of which have not been changed by the heat treatment”
ME32 says no

I can invent a new measure type “Import control for sieved fruit puree” … which is what the EU has done, and which we will also need to do in the future.

Quotas


Introduction to quotas


First Come, First Served Quotas


In-depth view of data tables


Licensed quotas


Quota user needs


Quota business rules


Introduction to quotas

A quota is used as a means of controlling the flow of goods into a country in order to create a balance between:


the needs of consumers or manufacturing industries that would use the item as a component or ingredient in producing something else in the importing countries and
domestic producers of the good, whose livelihood depends on producing and selling a product to domestic customers at full market price.

For example, tomatoes are imported into the European Union from Mediterranean countries and other places with temperate climates in order to satiate the needs of European citizens for tomatoes and sauces containing tomatoes. In Southern Europe, there are tomato growers for whom the overseas suppliers are rivals that threaten their livelihood.
In the UK, sheep farmers depend on selling their goods to a UK market hungry for lamb and lamb products; but there is not enough lamb in the UK to satisfy our needs, hence the need to import lamb from New Zealand and other countries.
This is a fine balance that needs to be managed carefully in order to support the needs of the two contrasting needs: the need for the nation to consume and need for domestic suppliers to make a living.
This is where quotas come in.


Get to know Peter Ungphakorn


Peter Ungphakorn was a senior information officer with the WTO Secretariat until 2015.
Since then he has moved into journalism, focusing mainly on international trade rules, agreements and institutions and fortunately making his knowledge available to the public via his Trade Beta Blog.
This blog contains very good, simple explainers (for seven and a half year-olds) on a number of topics, including quotas.




Read above about Tariff Rate Quotas (TRQs) (less so quantitative restrictions)
See also his blog on Meursing tables which simplifies an incredibly complex subject.

What is a quota?


A quota allows a certain volume of goods to be imported into a country at a reduced duty rate.
Once that volume has been imported, then the quota is considered to be exhausted and is no longer available to draw down against.
At that point, all importers will be forced to import the goods at the full (or less preferential duty rate).


What properties does a quota have?


Returning to the lamb quota on the previous screen, clicking on the term “092016” shows more detail of the quota.
“092016” is the quota order number. If any trader wants to take advantage of the preferential duties associated with a quota, then they need to quote that 6-digit quota order number on their import declaration. A quota1 has properties such as those shown here
These properties are described on the following pages


Defining quotas
There are multiple ways of defining and grouping quotas, all of which will be relevant to the delivery of the next iteration of the Tariff Application:


Administration mechanism:


First come first served 
Licensed

Legislative mechanism:


WTO quota
ATQ
preferential quota as part of an FTA 
safeguard quota

Origin quota: 


Yes
No


If you were to draw a Venn-style diagram of how these slices fit together, it would look a bit like this:

Preferential vs Non-Preferential quotas
Preferential quotas


The term preferential means that a single country or bloc is afforded treatment that provides better market access / lower duties than other countries.
In practical terms, preferential tariff duties and quotas are almost always made available via (Free) Trade Agreements. The quota is agreed as part of the bilateral negotiation between the two parties that provides each with mutual benefits.
Preferential quotas are always applied at a specific country or small group of countries.
Within the EU, there are a very small number of quotas which are applied to multiple countries (e.g. a wine quota available for imports from multiple W. Balkan countries), but most are aimed explicitly at one country or bloc.
Among the few exceptions, Greenland benefits from preferential quotas on seafoods outside of a formal Trade Agreement

Non-Preferential quotas


Non-preferential quotas are aimed at maintaining the balance of trade flows on critical goods by opening up a specific volume of market access to all overseas nations – in most cases, the non-preferential quotas are assigned to ERGA OMNES1 (the country group that includes all countries).
There are very few officially non-preferential quotas that have been opened up to specific countries only, where there is a need to maintain global trade flows with a less blunt instrument than a global non-preferential quota applied to the entire world, especially where there are trade titans in a particular commodity
Lamb is again a great example of this – there is a non-preferential quota for Erga Omnes (small volume) and much larger non-prefs for specific countries like Chile, Australia and New Zealand – each of which is a dominant player in the lamb trade.

Ways of administering quotas
There are two methods of administering a quota:
First Come First Served quotas


These are by far the most common of the two types of quota.
As the name suggests, a FCFS quota involves making a pot available to traders: whoever claims against that pot first gets to take advantage of the reduced rate.
If you’re not quick enough, you miss the opportunity and pay the non-preferential rate.

Licensed quotas


The purpose of a licensed quota is the same as a FCFS quota: to protect the fine balance of trade flows, however the mechanism for applying for usage is very different.
For each quota, periods of the year are opened up for importers to apply for licenses from the Rural Payments Agency (RPA) - a division of Defra.
During this period, the RPA accepts these license requests and issues licenses according to the specific rules of the quota
In the EU tariff, all licensed quotas’ 6-digit quota order numbers begin with “094”.

Origin quotas
Some quotas identify as Origin Quotas (about 25%)
Origin quotas allow for specific quantities of some products to receive preferential tariff treatment if the products meet certain conditions, for example a proof of origin can be provided to prove that the goods do in fact come from the specific country.
Origin quotas are always preferential in nature.
For a good example of an origin quota, please see the cat & dog food quota in place with Canada, where a proof of origin certificate is explicitly required.

The reason why this is important is that a quota’s origin status is displayed on the reference documents that accompany a trade agreements (as a schedule to the primary SI).
WTO quotas


The UK declares a tariff “schedule of concessions” to the WTO which is made up of multiple elements – what interests us most here is:
the tariff schedule
the schedules for tariff quotas on agricultural and non-agricultural products
The quota schedules list the concessions that we will make to overseas nations to provide greater market access to our market than would have been afforded by adopting the MFN rate alone.
In most cases, WTO quotas are assigned to the whole world (ERGA OMNES), but in certain cases (e.g. with lamb), the quota concessions are made available to individual countries which major in a certain trade (e.g. New Zealand for lamb).
Almost all WTO quotas are agricultural goods (this also applies to the other kinds of quota).


Autonomous quotas (ATQs)


Autonomous quotas are represented in the tariff as simple “Non-preferential quotas”. These are particularly applicable within the fishing industry. There is contention within the fishing industry between the catching sector and the food and processing sector.
For highly consumed goods, such as cod, pollock and prawns, the UK / EU catching industry cannot catch sufficient product to satisfy the needs of the home and international market. Therefore the processing industry needs access to low or zero duty for such products, while the catching industry needs protection by retaining at least some maximum import threshold above which normal tariff duties apply.
The autonomous tariff rate quota (ATQ) facilitates this compromise – a quantity of goods can be imported into the EU at zero or low rate, until exhausted, at which point the duty reverts to the third country rate
ATQs are set on a three year cycle: the ATQ duty rate cannot be changed in the course of that 3 year cycle, however the starting balance for each year can be assessed at the start of each year.
For fisheries ATQs, there is an additional point of interest, that, if 80% or more of the quota has been exhausted by the end of September in any given year, then the balance of the quota is increased by 20%
Autonomous Quotas so called, as the EU unilaterally decides to open a quota – there is no requirement for recourse to WTO approval to open an ATQ.
It is anticipated that the ATQs will continue to operate post-Brexit as they are favoured within the Defra ministry and offer a compromise to the different parts of the industry.

What products are covered by quotas?

Identifying quota types


Unfortunately, it is not a simple matter to take a quota order number and determine what kind of quota is being used. In the EU Tariff:


All current EU quota order numbers begin with 09 without exception
“094” means licensed quota
Autonomous agriculture quotas begin 0977
Autonomous fisheries quotas begin 0987

Apart from that, there are few obvious rules that define the EU’s use of quotas.
The system for identifying quotas in the UK tariff will be determined in the course of 2020.

Managing quota order numbers


DIT must take the lead in managing quota order numbers – this process has been introduced but not properly observed.
It needs to be a consultative process between DIT, HMRC and Defra to avoid errors and confusion, e.g. reusing existing quota order numbers
How quotas get set up is dependent on what they have been used for previously – we have inadvertently selected quota order numbers that were a cross section of closed and open quota order numbers, which have caused management challenges in previous migrations.
As of March 26th, the likelihood is that quota order numbers in the UK will be using ”08” as their first two digits to differentiate from the EU, with specific challenges around the dual Tariff in Northern Ireland being the primary cause. This remains to be agreed and properly analysed however.

First Come, First Served Quotas

First Come, First Served quotas are far more prevalent than licensed quotas on the Tariff database.
As the name suggests this favours those traders that apply for the quota first
Then, once the initial volume assigned to the quota has been fully depleted, the quota is deemed to be exhausted and is no longer available to draw down against. Once depleted, the trader’s import then falls back on the next best import duty, which may be a tariff preference, but it more likely just the MFN duty.
There is an important difference in the way in which FCFS are managed compared to licensed quotas:
FCFS quotas pass through the HMRC systems that are of greatest interest to the DIT Tariff Application (CHIEF and CDS)
Licensed quotas do not touch HMRC systems: instead they are handled essentially off-system via the RPA (see following slides)
The way in which the DIT application handles the different types of quotas is very different, as will be discussed.

NI Protocol has changed the approach to CDS migration and this impacts quotas
The NI Protocol requires (over-simplified):


all goods imported into Northern Ireland to be subject to EU regulatory controls in full
all goods considered to be at risk of entering the EU via the NI / ROI boundary to be subject to EU import duties
while those goods that are not at risk are subject to GB duties

This requires 2 tariffs to be present to work out the applicable duties based on the circumstances of the individual trade. This is too complex to do in CHIEF and a huge overhead to do in two systems concurrently anyway.
Therefore CDS is now designated solely for NI traders (plus the 10 traders that have already been migrated), whereas all other (GB) traders will remain on CHIEF until a future date (to be specified).
The impact on quotas is that, by extension, imports to NI of at risk goods may still claim on EU quotas, and these requests will continue to need to be allocated via the EU Quota 2 system while UK quotas will be allocated by the new CDS Quota Allocation Module (QAM). There is a strong possibility for confusion for traders if the UK continues to share the same quota order numbers as the EU.

The Taric and FCFS quotas
The data objects that are utilised for FCFS are vastly more numerous than those used for licensed quotas
Licensed quotas essentially use just measures not any of the other quota related tables. That is because all the other tables are set up uniquely to manage the set up and decrementing of quota balances.

The timespans of a FCFS quota


There are no limits on the periods that quotas can span, but there are commonalities, which these pages aim to share.
There are no quotas that are essentially one-offs – a quota is a permanent instrument to balance trade, not a one-time hit. The only slight deviation from this concerns the quotas that have been put in place to provide checks and balances on the import of steel goods (Steel safeguards), which evolve annually: this is just because the instrument is immature, not because it is a one-off.
The following types of quota periodicity can be found in the tariff:


Annual full year quota running from Jan 1st to December 31st and repeating every year
Annual full year quota running from another start date (e.g. July 1st to June 30th) and repeating every year
Part year quota running from any date to any other date (e.g. Feb 14th to May 31st) and repeating between the same dates every year
Quarterly quota running from Jan 1st to December 31st and repeating on that pattern every year
Quarterly quota running from another start date but lasting a full 12 months and repeating on that pattern every year
Part year quota split into monthly sections and repeating every year

These periods are enshrined in the legislation that engenders them – there is no deviation on the start and end dates of the periods (though watch out for leap years)

Impact of European growing seasons

There are more factors at play in determining quota volumes and periods than growing seasons (or marketing periods as they are called), but time of year is important for the EU, especially for Mediterranean countries.
In time, seasonality may be of less importance to the UK, as our climate does not (yet) suit the industrial levels of production seen in Southern Europe.
Quota staging


The ultimate goal of a trade agreement is often to get to a place where there is a 0% import duty on goods being imported
But, if that goal were to be reached immediately, the toxic shock to domestic producers would be potentially crippling, as  internal markets are swept away in one fell swoop by cheap and abundant imports.
Therefore the idea of staging has been adopted to allow domestic businesses to adjust to the new reality over time.
Staging periods equate to the period over which a trade agreement reaches it ultimate goal:


for tariff preferences, this is usually finite. For example, an agreement may include the goal to reduce an import duty from 10% (the pre-agreement MFN) to 0% over 4 years, reducing by 2.5% per year. After 4 years, the duty remains at 0% for as long as the agreement remains in place
for staging in quotas, there is no finite end goal, just an increase in the volume of goods made available to the quota. For example at the start of a trade agreement, a quota may permit the import of 100,000 KGM of goods at a reduced rate. The agreement states that an additional 10,000 KGM are permitted per year. I have not seen a ceiling placed on this (e.g. an extra 10,000 KGM a year until it reached 200,000 KGM), but that does not mean it does not happen. The relaxation always takes place against the quota volume, not against the in-quota duties.

Staging often appears in quotas created as part of a Trade Agreement, but never in WTO quotas or ATQs

Safeguard quotas


Since 2018, the EU has imposed quotas as part of its Steel Safeguards programme. Since 2017, USA has imposed swingeing import duties on steel and related goods coming into the country in order to protect its own industry from collapse
This led to a huge increase in the quantities of such goods coming into the European Union, as manufacturers (usually in the Far East), who previously had easy pickings in USA, now had to seek alternative markets.
The knock-on impact was felt in EU domestic steel suppliers, hence the imposition of steel safeguards by the EU.
Safeguards had been extremely rare in the EU until 2018 and the use of quotas to support them had never been seen. Now they are part of the EU’s defence armoury and will be adopted largely like-for-like by the UK after the end of the implementation period.
The safeguard works like this:


a punitive duty of 25% import duty (type 696 – Additional duties (safeguard)) is applied to multiple steel products grouped in 28 categories. The duty is applied to c. 100 countries
then individual quotas are overlaid to remove the duties for certain countries up to a given volume – different quotas are set up for each of the 28 groups (with many country exclusions), some of the quotas being annual and some of the quotas being quarterly

This function is documented in detail elsewhere – warning: it is hugely complex and warrants very detailed attention.
Knowing about the concepts behind quotas before digging into the safeguards will prepare you for the complexity.

Introductory periods


There are very many cases where an annual cadence is set up for a quota with an introductory period at the start that allows the quota to, for example, coincide with the Day One live implementation of a trade agreement, but to still allow the cadence to follow a marketing period.
This ‘introductory period’ will be critical also in the migration of quotas from the EU to the UK – if the implementation period ends on December 31st 2020, then there will be many quotas which will naturally start in the UK tariff on 1st January 2021, 


This is the mode (annual quotas that run for a calendar year).
But, any quota that does not commence on Jan 1st for its annual cadence will potentially require an introductory period
for example, an annual quota that starts on July 1st will require a 6-month introductory period
the steel safeguard quotas that typically run in quarters from July 1st to June 30th will require two introductory periods of three months each
but a quotas which runs from Valentine’s day to the end of June will not

      Criticality


As described above, the critical state determines if a trader needs to pay securities when utilising the quota.
The purpose of the requirement to collect securities is to


a) attempt to provide some sort of level playing field for traders as a quota reaches exhaustion
b) try to reduce returns towards the end of a definition’s active life span – managing returns is a hassle and if a trader has paid a security, the are less likely to be blasé with unused quota volume.

It is up to DIT to set the critical state of a quota definition, as we set all the properties of a quota definition period before it has begun, including critical state.
The rules of thumb are:
a new quota should be set to critical for three years so that there is an opportunity to study trade flows to determine if the volumes are correct
setting critical to ‘Y’ for this period ensures that the trade flow is more reflective of actual trade, dispensing with traders that declare a need for quota volume, but then do not use it.
BUT at the same time, for HMRC to take securities is a major overhead and they prefer not to in all cases.
So, during the 3 non-Brexits to date, the critical state for all quota definition periods has been set to N initially:


in order to reduce workload for HMRC
because most trade flows were fairly well known through UK;s membership of the EU
we were not introducing many genuinely new quotas (though the maxim was applied to all)

HMRC will need to be consulted in the lead-up to the implementation period on what they want to do with criticality: it is their domain, but our responsibility to set the initial state. This will be especially vital if we kick off any brand new trade deals with new overseas trading partners on Day One, which is remotely possible.

Managing geography

A FCFS quota only works when the full set of quota tables and measure tables are all set up and synchronised. It’s important to understand a few points around the geography of these two entities in order to create the right data.
* geography has to be set correctly against both the measure and the quota order number
* while the measures table has a 1-2-1 relationship with geographical areas, the quota order number table can relate to multiple origins via the many-to-many linking table “quota order number origins”.

Assigning quotas to countries


A quota can be assigned either to an individual country or to a group of countries
As described on the previous page, it may also be assigned to multiple (single) countries as well; theoretically, there is no reason why the quota cannot be assigned to multiple country groups simultaneously, though this has never happened.
There are currently (in the EU tariff) several quotas that are assigned to multiple (single) countries, but these will not carry over into the UK tariff (needs to be re-checked).


For example, quota order number 091530 is assigned to import of wines from the Western Balkan states of Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Kosovo, North Macedonia, Montenegro and Serbia.
While the UK will aim to engineer trade agreements with all 6 of these prior to the end of the implementation period, the quotas will be split into individual quotas per country.

The aim must be to still permit assignment of quotas to multiple countries however, as the model permits it.
For each assignment of geographical area to quota order number, the following is required:


a record in the measures table, linking geographical_area_id and ordernumber.
a record in the quota_order_number_origins table, linking geographical_area_id and quota_order_number_id.


Excluding countries from quotas


When a quota is assigned to a country group, it is possible and very common to exclude countries from that group, such that the quota does not apply to that country. Examples of this are:


quotas that apply on food and drink that apply to Central America, but from which Panama is excluded
almost all of the steel safeguard quotas feature multiple exclusions.

Obviously, the excluded country may be a member of the country group that’s assigned to the quota.
For each exclusion of a country from a quota associated to a country group, the following is required:


a record in the quota order number origin exclusions table, linking the origin and the excluded geographical area.
a record in the measure_excluded_geographical_areas table, linking the origin and the excluded geographical area.

Strategies for managing origins and exclusions


Quota order number origins have start dates and end dates
Quota order number origins do not have start dates and end dates
If you want to alter the quota order number origin exclusions for a quota, and you don’t want it to happen immediately, you cannot just add the exclusion to the origin: it will take effect immediately, which is almost certainly not the requirement.
As case in point is the steel safeguards:


each year to date, the origin exclusions have been tweaked as the EU has discovered more about world trade flows and the impact of both the US and EU safeguards on that flow
the EU has not been able to just remove and add exclusions

There are two options:


either end the origin and start another origin
or end the quota order number and start another quota order number with a new origin

The EU chooses the latter option: terminating the quota order number and replacing with another one starting the next day with a new origin.


in TAP1, we followed this route: the alternative route may also be followed.

      Licensed quota process – by example (garlic)


Possible garlic traders are grouped into two groups:


new importers – 30% of quota licenses are available for new importers
traditional importers – 70% of quota licenses are available for traditional importers (those who can prove they have imported garlic frequently over the last x years)
